00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:23.880
[Amit Varma]: Thanks so much, Amit. Great to be here. Madhav, as we, you know, before we begin talking about

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:29.360
[Amit Varma]: your book, tell me a little bit about your journey. Like, are you into law? Are you into

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:33.840
[Amit Varma]: history? How did sort of all of this happen where, you know, you got drawn to firstly

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:38.360
[Amit Varma]: this field and then to this specific subject of inquiry?

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:43.680
[Guest]: I studied law as an undergraduate at the National Law School in Bangalore, and I then studied

00:04:43.680 --> 00:04:50.200
[Guest]: law at the graduate level at Yale. And it became clear to me at some point that a lot

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:55.760
[Guest]: of the questions I was most interested in could not be answered entirely through legal

00:04:55.760 --> 00:05:01.440
[Guest]: training, that in some way law necessarily interacts with a set of other disciplines.

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:07.320
[Guest]: And because my primary interest was in constitutional law, the most obvious cognate field was political

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:13.640
[Guest]: theory, because constitutional law engages with politics in a profound way. And political

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:19.000
[Guest]: theory gives you the skills and the training and the knowledge to think about the deepest

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:25.520
[Guest]: questions in politics. And so it, it just it kind of became a natural step that I would

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:28.280
[Amit Varma]: go into a PhD in political theory.

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:32.400
[Amit Varma]: And you got into law, you got interested in political theory, but your book is also a

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:38.560
[Amit Varma]: book of history. So how does that happen when you realize that not just historical reading,

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:43.520
[Amit Varma]: but then if you want to also write about this, which is one way of expanding your own understanding,

00:05:43.520 --> 00:05:48.480
[Amit Varma]: then you also have to sort of get into history. How was that process? Did you come to history

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:51.800
[Amit Varma]: out of the love for history or out of necessity?

00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:58.360
[Guest]: I mean, I think I came to it actually out of an interest in thinking about how ideas

00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:03.920
[Guest]: had changed and had traveled over time. So when you're studying political theory, one

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:07.680
[Guest]: of the things that you think about, and when you're a student in those ways, is you think

00:06:07.680 --> 00:06:13.400
[Guest]: about certain concepts, right? Equality, freedom, democracy. And the interesting thing that

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:18.640
[Guest]: you might ask is, what do these terms mean over time? What do these terms mean to different

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:24.800
[Guest]: people? And so a lot of my questions began to have a historical texture to them, a historical

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:29.600
[Guest]: color to them. And so I wouldn't say that I'm a professional historian in the straightforward

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:34.080
[Guest]: sense of the term. But I would say that I'm somebody who's interested in the history of

00:06:34.080 --> 00:06:39.080
[Guest]: political thought, right? And so it's very much an intellectual history or a history

00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:44.480
[Guest]: of ideas that really, in some sense, sparked my curiosity.

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:49.680
[Amit Varma]: And who are the sort of the thinkers who influenced you? Or as you, you know, got deeper and deeper

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:54.040
[Amit Varma]: into these subjects, what are the books that you looked at as models of the kind of work

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:55.280
[Amit Varma]: that you'd like to do?

00:06:55.280 --> 00:07:01.200
[Guest]: I think if one thinks about India, in particular, I think the most familiar thinkers who we

00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:07.040
[Guest]: have, who do a kind of intellectual history or history of political thought, are people

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:14.120
[Guest]: like Pratap Bhanu Mehta, Sunil Khilnani, Nija Gopal Jayal. And I think slightly more limited

00:07:14.120 --> 00:07:19.760
[Guest]: to the scholarly domain and less familiar in popular writing is somebody like Sudipto

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:24.880
[Guest]: Kaviraj. And what all of these people are doing in some way is to think about, look,

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:30.880
[Guest]: you have a concept. And what does that concept mean to specific people at particular moments

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:39.120
[Guest]: in time? And how can we recover certain understandings of that concept? If I actually can read about

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:45.200
[Guest]: what somebody like Nehru thought about citizenship, can that help me think about citizenship today?

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:50.040
[Guest]: Right? Can that actually elucidate the concept in some way? And I think each of these people

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:58.520
[Guest]: have done that. And so Sunil's idea of India is just a marvelous attempt to think about

00:07:58.520 --> 00:08:06.560
[Guest]: the particular idea of democracy or the particular idea of how you domesticate a certain ideal

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:12.400
[Guest]: within a broader public life and within political history. I think Nija's book on citizenship,

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:18.720
[Guest]: for example, is a way to think about varying definitions and conceptions of citizenship

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:23.360
[Guest]: over 100 years, right? And she is a political theorist, but it's a history of ideas, which

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:28.120
[Guest]: is what she's interested in. And Pratap, we read week after week, who's attempting to

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:29.120
[Guest]: do that.

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:33.360
[Amit Varma]: Sadanand Pratap is absolutely India's finest public intellectual, I think. And just referring

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:37.920
[Amit Varma]: to Nija's book, you know, I hadn't read it until I was going to do an episode on citizenship

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:41.920
[Amit Varma]: with our mutual friend Srinath. And it spoke so much to the current time. Suddenly your

00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:47.120
[Amit Varma]: expanding of the current time just explodes and you get everything so much better because

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:52.180
[Amit Varma]: of a book like that. I also want to ask you about your reading and your writing. To begin

00:08:52.180 --> 00:08:57.520
[Amit Varma]: with reading, like, you know, I often get asked, how do I read so many books? And you

00:08:57.520 --> 00:09:03.080
[Amit Varma]: know, do I take notes, do I scheme, etc, etc. And you obviously read far more than me. I

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:06.880
[Amit Varma]: mean, while reading your book, one of the joys of reading your book was the ability

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:10.720
[Amit Varma]: to go to the footnotes and discover other things through that. And, you know, and I

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:16.000
[Amit Varma]: think any good book of history or nonfiction gives you that. So how do you read, you know,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.560
[Amit Varma]: do you have to ever force yourself to read? Has the nature of the way you read changed

00:09:20.560 --> 00:09:25.640
[Amit Varma]: since you became a scholar and a student yourself? Is there a difference between how you read

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:29.760
[Amit Varma]: for work and how you read for pleasure? What's your relationship with books like?

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:35.680
[Guest]: I think, at least to me, I feel I read quite badly, right? I feel I don't read enough,

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:43.080
[Guest]: and I don't concentrate enough when I read. But I think I don't read in very long spurts,

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:51.800
[Guest]: I actually lose attention relatively quickly. But I try very hard to actually read very

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:56.600
[Guest]: seriously and very carefully when I read. And so I normally never really need to read

00:09:56.600 --> 00:09:57.600
[Guest]: twice.

00:09:57.600 --> 00:09:59.320
[Guest]: And do you take notes and stuff while reading?

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:05.200
[Guest]: I do take notes. I do take notes sometimes. And sometimes I just have page numbers. But

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:12.840
[Guest]: I often am able to grasp what I'm reading with relative ease, if I am in the right frame

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:16.840
[Guest]: of mind. The challenge is in getting into that frame of mind and is actually taking

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:24.720
[Guest]: out a sufficient amount of time to being able to read. I think, in some ways, the hard chat,

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:29.320
[Guest]: the hard, I mean, in our lives now today, right, it's quite hard to actually be able

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:33.200
[Guest]: to turn off the internet and turn off the mobile phone, and then just say, okay, I'm

00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:38.240
[Guest]: having an hour of completely uninterrupted reading, which is the kind of thing that I

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:44.080
[Guest]: hope for. I think the other thing that can sometimes be challenging is that you don't

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:49.280
[Guest]: often know what to read. Right. And so even with this book, for example, part of what

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:55.880
[Guest]: was difficult was, we've only had one book on India's constitutional founding before

00:10:55.880 --> 00:11:01.640
[Guest]: this. And so there were moments where on different themes, I just, I didn't know actually what

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:08.480
[Guest]: to read. And then you just read more and you get to know what to read. Right. But I, my

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:14.680
[Guest]: life in terms of reading is not profoundly structured. I think I read a lot, I read less

00:11:14.680 --> 00:11:20.960
[Guest]: than I would like to, probably more than I think I do. But it's, it's disorganized, it's

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:24.680
[Guest]: profoundly disorganized, and I think it could be much better.

00:11:24.680 --> 00:11:29.720
[Amit Varma]: And when it comes to writing, a lot of academic writing is just hard to read, and it's dense

00:11:29.720 --> 00:11:34.560
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth. Your book obviously isn't that. In fact, there were parts while

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:38.480
[Amit Varma]: I was reading this book, and I think I told you this before the recording and you were

00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:42.320
[Amit Varma]: slightly embarrassed by it. There were times when I felt the quality of your prose reminded

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:46.200
[Amit Varma]: me of Pratap, which is the highest praise I can give really, in the sense that you're

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:51.440
[Amit Varma]: packing in a lot of thought and a lot of material into, you know, with a tremendous amount of

00:11:51.440 --> 00:11:57.640
[Amit Varma]: clarity. And even though you also write long sentences like Pratap often does, you know,

00:11:57.640 --> 00:12:02.000
[Amit Varma]: they're not unwieldy and long winding, they're packing in a lot, it all makes complete sense.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:06.960
[Amit Varma]: So is that, you know, is prose style something that you thought consciously about on your

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:09.720
[Amit Varma]: journey to becoming a writer on these matters?

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:15.280
[Guest]: Yes, and I'm actually really flattered and humbled that you would identify the prose

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:21.160
[Guest]: as being good because I, so I spent a lot of time rewriting this book, frankly, a lot

00:12:21.160 --> 00:12:26.400
[Guest]: of time, and I spent a lot of time removing huge amounts in it. And so the final book

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:34.040
[Guest]: actually had about 20-25%, even maybe 30% less than I had lying around. And the hope

00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:40.800
[Guest]: was and the aim was that look, I much rather just say less than more. And some of that

00:12:40.800 --> 00:12:45.720
[Guest]: is laziness, some of that is just a way to like intellectually flirt with ideas. But

00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:52.760
[Guest]: I also just didn't want to overwrite. And I am very interested in how people write and

00:12:52.760 --> 00:12:58.160
[Guest]: in what and rather than just what they write. And so I care a lot about that. And most of

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:01.040
[Guest]: the writers I admire are just beautiful writers.

00:13:01.040 --> 00:13:02.040
[Guest]: Like?

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:07.800
[Guest]: I mean, I think Sunil is a great example. I think globally, I love David Bromwich's

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:14.720
[Guest]: writing. I read him regularly. And just there are a range of nonfiction writers who just

00:13:14.720 --> 00:13:20.800
[Guest]: who are genuine stylists. Right. And so I think that that's, I don't know if the if

00:13:20.800 --> 00:13:26.440
[Guest]: the book has that, but certainly I aspired to make at least parts of it beautiful to

00:13:26.440 --> 00:13:27.440
[Amit Varma]: read.

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:32.320
[Amit Varma]: We're going to move on to the book now. And let's sort of move on to the conception of

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:36.700
[Amit Varma]: India itself and the role that our founders played in thinking about it. And you begin

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:42.080
[Amit Varma]: your book with a quote from Nehru, where he says, one of the unfortunate legacies of the

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:47.840
[Amit Varma]: past has been that there has been no imagination in the understanding of the Indian problem.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:50.360
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. So what is this Indian problem?

00:13:50.360 --> 00:13:55.180
[Guest]: It's an interesting quote, if you think about it, right? I mean, it's the quote comes up,

00:13:55.180 --> 00:14:01.600
[Guest]: the moment comes up in the Constituent Assembly, Nehru is speaking, and he's suddenly saying

00:14:01.600 --> 00:14:09.360
[Guest]: that, look, actually, we aren't grappling with the situation that we are in, because

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:14.920
[Guest]: nobody really has realized the challenge before the Constituent Assembly. And it's an odd

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:19.880
[Guest]: thing to say, right? Because if you think that if you were to guess anything, you would

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:25.160
[Guest]: say that nobody would have a deeper sense of the situation than those people there.

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:29.960
[Guest]: And for Nehru, the Indian problem was, and it's interesting also that he calls it the

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:33.320
[Guest]: Indian problem, right? So the first thing to say about that is that he sees something

00:14:33.320 --> 00:14:37.920
[Guest]: distinctive going on, right? It's not just the problem of another country or the problem

00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:42.620
[Guest]: of some particular idea. It's actually an Indian problem that no country has previously

00:14:42.620 --> 00:14:48.280
[Guest]: been asked to solve. And the Indian problem for him is the problem of how do you create

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:57.480
[Guest]: democracy in a place without its preconditions? So you have internalized for well over a century

00:14:57.480 --> 00:15:04.960
[Guest]: that there is actually a certain set of circumstances that make democracy possible. And India doesn't

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:09.480
[Guest]: have those circumstances, and yet it needs to become a democracy. And how do you then

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:10.720
[Guest]: address that problem?

00:15:10.720 --> 00:15:15.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and you also at one point, and I like the phrasing of this, you put you point out

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:20.640
[Amit Varma]: you talk about the suggestion that human behavior was not the consequence of politics, but instead

00:15:20.640 --> 00:15:27.600
[Amit Varma]: its cause, stop quote. And later on, you ask the question in the context of the Hobbesian

00:15:27.600 --> 00:15:32.760
[Amit Varma]: project, quote, did politics produce these spaces of energy, these fresh ways of thinking

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:38.000
[Amit Varma]: about freedom, or was politics contingent on them, stop quote. And these seem to feed

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:44.000
[Amit Varma]: into Nehru's question in a sense of what Nehru really seems to be asking is that look, we

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.560
[Amit Varma]: have to now move towards being a democracy, but none of those conditions are there, most

00:15:48.560 --> 00:15:54.640
[Amit Varma]: particularly the democratic citizen isn't there. So in the act of creating this democracy,

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:59.280
[Amit Varma]: can we create that democratic citizen? And is the constitution the tool to do that? Am

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:03.160
[Amit Varma]: I right in saying that this is a fundamental sort of question?

00:16:03.160 --> 00:16:07.280
[Guest]: That's right. And just to go back to the part that you read, I mean, the way to think about

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:13.680
[Guest]: it is this, right? After the 19th century, you have around you three things going on.

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:19.480
[Guest]: You have politics as some space, right? You have the economy as some space, and you have

00:16:19.480 --> 00:16:26.520
[Guest]: society as some space. And all these three are slightly governed by a kind of different

00:16:26.520 --> 00:16:32.200
[Guest]: logic, right? So society say might have its own kind of relations, it might have its own

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:37.480
[Guest]: kind of power dynamics, it might have its own kind of freedom. The market, again, has

00:16:37.480 --> 00:16:42.440
[Guest]: its own kind of logic, its own kind of structures, its own kind of opportunities. And then there's

00:16:42.440 --> 00:16:47.480
[Guest]: politics, which is again governed by its own rationality. And this distinction between

00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:53.800
[Guest]: the three really comes out in the 19th century, both with the Industrial Revolution, and with

00:16:53.800 --> 00:17:01.600
[Guest]: the birth of actually sociology. And what happens for people is that they begin to ask,

00:17:01.600 --> 00:17:06.360
[Guest]: and it's a natural question, it's not coming out of deep seated Western racism, it's actually

00:17:06.360 --> 00:17:12.320
[Guest]: coming out of a very honest inquiry. They begin to ask that, look, is politics going

00:17:12.320 --> 00:17:19.440
[Guest]: to rest on how these other spaces are? Or is actually politics producing these spaces?

00:17:19.440 --> 00:17:27.160
[Guest]: Is the caste system the consequence of the political structure we inhabit? Or is the

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:33.240
[Guest]: political structure we inhabit going to take a certain shape because of the caste system?

00:17:33.240 --> 00:17:39.480
[Guest]: And that is not an easy question to answer, right? And the British answer to that was

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:44.720
[Guest]: look, because India has a certain kind of society, it can only have a certain kind of

00:17:44.720 --> 00:17:50.440
[Guest]: government, right? And the Nehruvian sort of answer, which places politics front and

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:57.400
[Guest]: center, and the Indian answer, right, is that look, actually, everything that you've gotten

00:17:57.400 --> 00:18:03.920
[Guest]: is because of the politics that you've had. People are behaving in a certain way, because

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:09.360
[Guest]: you've actually put them in structures where they will behave in that way. And a version

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:15.120
[Guest]: of it, for example, is, you know, in contemporary India, just to sort of switch for a moment,

00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:22.280
[Guest]: sometimes people will say, look, there are communal people, this is why we have a communal

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:28.000
[Guest]: politics, right? And one answer to that is, actually, you run a communal politics, you

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:33.920
[Guest]: get a communal people. You run a secular politics, you get a secular people, right? And that's

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:37.180
[Guest]: kind of the answer here, in some ways.

00:18:37.180 --> 00:18:41.200
[Amit Varma]: So there are sort of two aspects to this, which I find interesting. One, of course,

00:18:41.200 --> 00:18:47.000
[Amit Varma]: is that I would sort of agree with Nehru that obviously, though he would not have phrased

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.840
[Amit Varma]: it like this, but people respond to incentives. So if you create a form of government that

00:18:50.840 --> 00:18:55.520
[Amit Varma]: creates certain sets of incentives, people will necessarily respond to that. In fact,

00:18:55.520 --> 00:19:00.480
[Amit Varma]: my thesis of, you know, Jagdish Bhagwati had once said that Indians are more into rent

00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:05.600
[Amit Varma]: seeking while the Chinese are intuitively more into profit seeking. And that sense of

00:19:05.600 --> 00:19:09.420
[Amit Varma]: why Indians are more into rent seeking, that is, we are always looking for ways to make

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:14.360
[Amit Varma]: a fast buck or cheat someone or whatever, is that because the oppressive state made

00:19:14.360 --> 00:19:19.540
[Amit Varma]: it so hard for so many decades to earn an honest living. And because it was the easiest

00:19:19.540 --> 00:19:24.240
[Amit Varma]: way to make money was through rent seeking and was through sort of becoming a part of

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:28.160
[Amit Varma]: that structure. People instinctively think in those terms. And you could say that as

00:19:28.160 --> 00:19:32.940
[Amit Varma]: people responding to the incentives of the system of governance upon them, and this can

00:19:32.940 --> 00:19:36.560
[Amit Varma]: work in the other direction. I mean, I give a negative example, but this can work in the

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:42.400
[Amit Varma]: other way also where you can promote fraternity and, you know, much more tolerance just through

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:46.600
[Amit Varma]: what the law happens to be and how it's all structured. But the counterpoint to that would

00:19:46.600 --> 00:19:51.520
[Amit Varma]: be that, you know, and a point at where Gandhi, for example, disagreed with Nehru and Ambedkar

00:19:51.520 --> 00:19:55.760
[Amit Varma]: and where conservatives would disagree, and you had the same argument playing out elsewhere

00:19:55.760 --> 00:20:01.240
[Amit Varma]: between Burke and Paine and so on, is that Gandhi sort of felt that the locus of change

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:06.720
[Amit Varma]: was society itself, that change would only happen bottom up. And Nehru and Ambedkar,

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:12.440
[Amit Varma]: on the other hand, felt that no, you know, it's the diseases such as I mean, caste is

00:20:12.440 --> 00:20:17.680
[Amit Varma]: a disease in our society. And the diseases are so deeply rooted, that that change cannot

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:23.880
[Amit Varma]: happen from the bottom up, the state has to sort of lead the way. And so this is the sort

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:27.880
[Amit Varma]: of debate that's playing. This is one of the fundamental debates that you've sort of identified

00:20:27.880 --> 00:20:33.800
[Guest]: playing out, isn't it? Absolutely. I think that debates about a strong centralized state

00:20:33.800 --> 00:20:40.160
[Guest]: in the ultimate analysis are debates about very different conceptions of Indian society.

00:20:40.160 --> 00:20:47.280
[Guest]: Right. So Ambedkar and Nehru are fierce critics of Ambedkar of Indian society. And it's in

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:53.320
[Guest]: part their criticism of Indian society that makes them so radical. Gandhi, on the other

00:20:53.320 --> 00:20:59.960
[Guest]: hand, is to an extent critical of the practices of Indian society. But he also believes that

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:04.800
[Guest]: the change will come from within, that the change has to come from within. And that actually

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:13.240
[Guest]: enduring change will rest on certain kinds of practices. It will rest on genuine examples

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:19.040
[Guest]: that you have to provide in your social life that will pave the way. And both of them,

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:26.520
[Guest]: therefore, there isn't really a meeting point for people whose presuppositions are so distinct

00:21:26.520 --> 00:21:30.440
[Guest]: about the dynamic and the theory of historical change.

00:21:30.440 --> 00:21:34.320
[Amit Varma]: And one question I've asked many guests on the show, so it will almost seem like a cliche

00:21:34.320 --> 00:21:39.400
[Amit Varma]: to my listeners, is something that I feel you're best equipped to answer, which is that

00:21:39.400 --> 00:21:44.120
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me that what we did, and that speaks to this earlier debate, which we mentioned,

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:49.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, between conservatives and people who would want to use the state to transform

00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:53.400
[Amit Varma]: society, which is that what we seem to have done is we seem to have imposed a liberal

00:21:53.400 --> 00:22:01.480
[Amit Varma]: constitution on an illiberal society. And one could ask, is that imposition itself liberal,

00:22:01.480 --> 00:22:06.600
[Amit Varma]: but a more pertinent question in current times when many people say that society has caught

00:22:06.600 --> 00:22:12.840
[Amit Varma]: up with politics and that our illiberal society is now reflected in the sort of politics that

00:22:12.840 --> 00:22:18.840
[Amit Varma]: we have, is that can such top-down imposition of values ever actually work?

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:23.880
[Guest]: So that's a very packed question, right? And let's separate it at multiple levels. So the

00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:30.520
[Guest]: first thing to think about is, do we actually think it's true that we've imposed a liberal

00:22:30.520 --> 00:22:37.000
[Guest]: constitution on a people who are not liberal? Because the word imposed there is very interesting,

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:42.880
[Guest]: right? And I'm not sure that it's actually a very good word to use for the following

00:22:42.880 --> 00:22:49.840
[Guest]: reason. On the one hand, clearly the people who were in the Constituent Assembly had a

00:22:49.840 --> 00:22:54.680
[Guest]: vision of India that was not the current vision of India. That is the whole Indian problem,

00:22:54.680 --> 00:22:59.640
[Guest]: right? They needed to create democracy and India was not filled with democratic values

00:22:59.640 --> 00:23:06.160
[Guest]: and constitutional principles. In that sense, they were radicals, they were revolutionary.

00:23:06.160 --> 00:23:11.640
[Guest]: But the Constituent Assembly enjoyed extraordinary political legitimacy, even though the body

00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:18.040
[Guest]: was not actually voted in through universal adult franchise. It was unquestioned in its

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:25.800
[Guest]: authority and in its leadership. In that sense, imposed has a slightly more authoritarian

00:23:25.800 --> 00:23:32.400
[Guest]: cast to it, which I'm not sure actually is accurate given the real power that the Assembly

00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:36.960
[Guest]: enjoyed. In fact, if the Assembly didn't enjoy that power, you wouldn't have gotten the constitution.

00:23:36.960 --> 00:23:41.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's not power, but I'd say the key word there is not power, but legitimacy. And

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:45.200
[Amit Varma]: I'm willing to concede that it had legitimacy, that these were the recognized leaders of

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:50.480
[Amit Varma]: the day. They had won elections before under the British. So, I don't have an issue with

00:23:50.480 --> 00:23:54.000
[Amit Varma]: that. But I think that any constitution they came up with would have been an imposition,

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:58.960
[Amit Varma]: not necessarily this one and a necessary imposition because there's no other way of doing it.

00:23:58.960 --> 00:24:03.560
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, so we can quibble about whether the word imposition is right, right? I'm just

00:24:03.560 --> 00:24:08.240
[Guest]: not sure. I'm not sure whether it's the correct word. And I think the other thing that we

00:24:08.240 --> 00:24:14.400
[Guest]: need to remember is this, that the constitution puts forth a really relaxed procedure for

00:24:14.400 --> 00:24:22.560
[Guest]: amendment, a really relaxed procedure for change. The constitution is given in 1950.

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:28.640
[Guest]: In 1951, you have elections, the whole country can vote. For the first time in human history,

00:24:28.640 --> 00:24:33.320
[Guest]: you're granted universal adult franchise under these conditions. And the body that is voted

00:24:33.320 --> 00:24:39.200
[Guest]: in could have gotten rid of the constitution. So, in that sense, it's a genuinely democratic

00:24:39.200 --> 00:24:47.480
[Guest]: moment, right? And the second question, right, which is that look, actually, has society

00:24:47.480 --> 00:24:53.480
[Guest]: caught up with politics? I actually think, ironically enough, the present moment reveals

00:24:53.480 --> 00:25:01.000
[Guest]: just the opposite. I think the Indian founding was built on the idea that to be in the modern

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:07.440
[Guest]: world, right, as opposed to to be in the ancient world, or to be in the medieval world, means

00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:13.120
[Guest]: that your world can be entirely constructed. It means that when Amit Verma is born, he

00:25:13.120 --> 00:25:21.520
[Guest]: could be any type of person. His job, his identity, his role in life are subject to

00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:28.840
[Guest]: change at an individual level. And the whole world can be made and remade. And what politics

00:25:28.840 --> 00:25:34.480
[Guest]: offers us is a way to make and remake our world through nonviolent means, right, unlike

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:41.360
[Guest]: war. Now, the interesting thing about the current moment is that actually, I think even

00:25:41.360 --> 00:25:45.760
[Guest]: though the current Indian, the dominant mode of Indian politics at the moment, the Hindu

00:25:45.760 --> 00:25:50.640
[Guest]: nationalist movement is very different from the founding vision, and could not be more

00:25:50.640 --> 00:25:55.880
[Guest]: different from the founding vision. They share this belief that the world can be entirely

00:25:55.880 --> 00:26:01.760
[Guest]: remade, because they are actually attempting to remake it. If they didn't want to remake

00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:05.680
[Guest]: it, if they didn't actually think that if they didn't act, if they thought that the

00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:10.200
[Guest]: world was already like this, then there's no need to remake it. And if they thought

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:14.000
[Guest]: that it could not be remade this way, then there's no need to remake it. They believe

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:19.040
[Guest]: in the absolutism and the primacy of politics, as much as anything. It's why they are changing

00:26:19.040 --> 00:26:24.800
[Amit Varma]: our laws. So isn't this belief in remaking the world actually a very dangerous belief?

00:26:24.800 --> 00:26:30.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we've seen this in the 20th century and Mao and Hitler and Stalin and so on. And

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:34.600
[Amit Varma]: in fact, when Modi did demonetization, I compared it with the Mao's Great Leap Forward and what

00:26:34.600 --> 00:26:39.440
[Amit Varma]: Mao did with the Sparrows. You know, isn't this kind of social engineering always doomed

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:44.840
[Amit Varma]: to fail and equally disrespectful of the society you're claiming to represent? For example,

00:26:44.840 --> 00:26:49.320
[Amit Varma]: just as you said, if I may add to that, just as you said that the founders of our constitution

00:26:49.320 --> 00:26:54.000
[Amit Varma]: were radicals, in a similar sense, it could be argued that the Hindu nationalist movement

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:58.960
[Amit Varma]: today are also radicals, because they are chipping away at the tolerance and inclusiveness

00:26:58.960 --> 00:27:01.840
[Amit Varma]: that is such an inherent part of our society.

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:06.160
[Guest]: I think that that's right. I think that in the way they are radicals, I think that it

00:27:06.160 --> 00:27:11.160
[Guest]: doesn't mean that you're disrespecting society because it's all done through social legitimacy.

00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:17.200
[Guest]: So I don't think that's quite right. I think that the question isn't, is it dangerous or

00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:23.000
[Guest]: not? It is dangerous, Amit, because in the same way as it is dangerous to rule yourselves.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:28.720
[Guest]: That's what it means to be independent. That's what it means to have freedom. When I look

00:27:28.720 --> 00:27:33.760
[Guest]: at you and I say, Amit Verma, you can have any career you want, if you work hard, and

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:38.920
[Guest]: I give you the right education and you pick your career. Is that dangerous? Yes. You could

00:27:38.920 --> 00:27:43.640
[Amit Varma]: do a terrible job with it. No, I think there's a conflation here. My belief in individual

00:27:43.640 --> 00:27:51.640
[Amit Varma]: rights and in my agency to shape my own destiny is very different from the freedom of a society

00:27:51.640 --> 00:27:58.040
[Amit Varma]: to sort of or the freedom of a political class to transform society through laws.

00:27:58.040 --> 00:28:02.520
[Guest]: But I think that that's what it means to be democratic. It's collective agency. The question

00:28:02.520 --> 00:28:09.240
[Guest]: then is twofold. Firstly, what are the processes by which we engineer? Right. And so, for instance,

00:28:09.240 --> 00:28:16.000
[Guest]: the Indian founding is a dramatic effort to engineer things through civil, nonviolent

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:22.480
[Guest]: means. Right. So even things like modernization, which I discuss in the book, they are clearly

00:28:22.480 --> 00:28:28.000
[Guest]: impressed by and who wouldn't be at the time by Soviet Russia's extraordinary economic

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:32.160
[Guest]: growth. But they think that there are serious problems with the means and we care about

00:28:32.160 --> 00:28:36.520
[Guest]: the means because the means themselves are constitutive of freedom. So there's one question,

00:28:36.520 --> 00:28:40.680
[Guest]: which is the question of how are you engineering? And the second question is, to what end are

00:28:40.680 --> 00:28:46.480
[Guest]: you engineering? And are you actually engineering towards an end that still treats people as

00:28:46.480 --> 00:28:52.720
[Guest]: free and equal beings? Because the whole purpose of actually giving freedom is that you're

00:28:52.720 --> 00:28:57.760
[Guest]: treating people as free and equal beings in some way. Right. And so I think that the danger

00:28:57.760 --> 00:29:01.800
[Guest]: of the present moment isn't that they're trying to remake the world. I think everybody's trying

00:29:01.800 --> 00:29:07.320
[Guest]: to remake the world. In fact, I think that the most gratifying and reassuring thing about

00:29:07.320 --> 00:29:13.400
[Guest]: politics is that it can be a space for possibility. I think what's scary is how they are doing

00:29:13.400 --> 00:29:20.280
[Guest]: it and what they are doing it towards. Right. In fact, I think it's not only and I think

00:29:20.280 --> 00:29:26.800
[Guest]: what that captures is that in politics, Amit, what's dangerous is not only extremism, but

00:29:26.800 --> 00:29:33.760
[Guest]: cynicism. I think it's cynicism above all. And I think on India's left, for example,

00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:39.400
[Guest]: or on India's a lot of other Indian political spectrum, that's the danger. Right. For instance,

00:29:39.400 --> 00:29:44.560
[Guest]: why is our caste arrangement moved from a constitutional arrangement that wanted to

00:29:44.560 --> 00:29:49.800
[Guest]: transcend caste to a situation now where it is simply power sharing between different

00:29:49.800 --> 00:29:56.080
[Guest]: caste groups? Because you don't think caste can be eradicated. So that's cynicism. And

00:29:56.080 --> 00:30:00.680
[Guest]: that's actually what's dangerous. So what's dangerous isn't that these guys want to change

00:30:00.680 --> 00:30:06.560
[Guest]: the world. What's dangerous is what they want to change it to and how they plan to change

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:13.240
[Amit Varma]: it. Well, yeah, I mean, but that's also a disagreement on ends and not so much a disagreement

00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:19.080
[Amit Varma]: on means. Let's kind of get back to your book where you write about where you know how one

00:30:19.080 --> 00:30:24.720
[Amit Varma]: of the fundamental decisions in hindsight, it kind of we take it so much for granted.

00:30:24.720 --> 00:30:30.800
[Amit Varma]: But one of the unusual decisions that was debated and was a question of universal suffrage.

00:30:30.800 --> 00:30:35.320
[Amit Varma]: That's right. Tell me a little bit about the contours of that particular debate. So I think

00:30:35.320 --> 00:30:38.760
[Guest]: to think about that, I mean, what we need to think about is that look, in the middle

00:30:38.760 --> 00:30:47.280
[Guest]: of the 20th century, you have to be really audacious to think that India can be a democracy.

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:54.560
[Guest]: A for 100 years, you've had this kind of political theory and philosophy. You've had this imperial

00:30:54.560 --> 00:31:01.760
[Guest]: vision that India cannot rule itself. Then you've had alongside that, right, a real life

00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:09.720
[Guest]: experience of democracy going wrong. So the only moment in world history where democratization

00:31:09.720 --> 00:31:16.160
[Guest]: and constitution making occur simultaneously is in Europe during the interwar period. And

00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:21.560
[Guest]: all of those countries collapse. All of those countries actually don't end up becoming democracies,

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:26.880
[Guest]: right, in a sustainable way. And so there are very good reasons and India's founding

00:31:26.880 --> 00:31:32.920
[Guest]: to think, look, democracy isn't really a very good system to go for. And they still go for

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:40.520
[Guest]: it, right. And I think that they go for it for a variety of reasons, right? One, I think

00:31:40.520 --> 00:31:48.520
[Guest]: there is genuinely a mass movement behind independence. Second, there is the sense that

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:54.440
[Guest]: actually this is what freedom means. There is a deep ideological conception that look,

00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:59.320
[Guest]: in an earlier generation, in the late 18th century, when you had the American and French

00:31:59.320 --> 00:32:02.800
[Guest]: revolutions, you didn't have to worry about how certain people will vote because you didn't

00:32:02.800 --> 00:32:09.320
[Guest]: give them the vote. Now, actually, they think that look, that can't mean freedom. Freedom

00:32:09.320 --> 00:32:13.000
[Guest]: can't just mean that I'm free from Britain, but I'm not giving my Indians the vote. And

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.840
[Guest]: there's a sense that look, in the Indian context, actually, what does that mean? In fact, there's

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:21.600
[Guest]: a great moment in the Constituent Assembly debates, I think, where Aladi Krishnaswami

00:32:21.600 --> 00:32:26.960
[Guest]: Iyer says, look, what does it mean to limit suffrage in a country where most people are

00:32:26.960 --> 00:32:29.280
[Guest]: poor? That means nobody will have suffrage at all.

00:32:29.280 --> 00:32:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think his point, as you've quoted him in the book is that if you, you know,

00:32:33.920 --> 00:32:37.840
[Amit Varma]: qualifications based on property or education are impossible, because most people have neither.

00:32:37.840 --> 00:32:43.240
[Guest]: Exactly. And I think it's but it's also the deep seated ideological vision, that actually,

00:32:43.240 --> 00:32:49.560
[Guest]: if you put people in a certain kind of system, you will get democratic people, that actually,

00:32:49.560 --> 00:32:55.080
[Guest]: you will create democratic citizens through the practices of democracy, that itself will

00:32:55.080 --> 00:33:02.480
[Guest]: provide the education necessary. And therefore, it doesn't mean that certain facts are false,

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:07.160
[Guest]: right. So of course, it's true that India is a diverse place. It has many religions

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:11.840
[Guest]: that is true, both for the British and for now. The question is, what does that mean

00:33:11.840 --> 00:33:17.480
[Guest]: for political life? Right? And the answer is, actually, it may not mean anything, you

00:33:17.480 --> 00:33:22.720
[Guest]: can still see each other as equal people, if you put them in a politics that shapes

00:33:22.720 --> 00:33:26.920
[Guest]: them as equal people. And so at the heart of the book, I think, and at the heart of

00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:33.360
[Guest]: the Indian founding, is the sentiment that look, representation will create its own reality.

00:33:33.360 --> 00:33:38.960
[Guest]: The minute you represent people in a certain way, the minute you actually put them in a

00:33:38.960 --> 00:33:46.000
[Guest]: kind of constitutional, legal, institutional model, that represents them in a certain way,

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.720
[Guest]: you will actually get the people you represent.

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:53.440
[Amit Varma]: And this struck me as one of the sort of profound insights that I learned from your book, which

00:33:53.440 --> 00:33:59.560
[Amit Varma]: is that the framers of the constitution looked at it as a pedagogical tool. It wasn't simply

00:33:59.560 --> 00:34:03.160
[Amit Varma]: a question of saying, okay, we have to govern and therefore we will have a constitution

00:34:03.160 --> 00:34:08.360
[Amit Varma]: that sets the rules of the game. Instead, the impetus is that through this constitution,

00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:12.600
[Amit Varma]: because people respond to incentives, and again, that's my language, not theirs, obviously,

00:34:12.600 --> 00:34:16.560
[Amit Varma]: that through this constitution, because people respond to incentives into the system that

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:21.360
[Amit Varma]: they are part of, if we frame a constitution correctly, then the citizen can learn to see

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:26.960
[Amit Varma]: himself as a democratic citizen, and equal to all other citizens, you know, therefore

00:34:26.960 --> 00:34:33.960
[Amit Varma]: invalidating other sort of forms of identity that might otherwise exist. And therefore,

00:34:33.960 --> 00:34:41.160
[Amit Varma]: in that framing, it's important to embody that sort of conception of how the founders

00:34:41.160 --> 00:34:46.640
[Amit Varma]: saw the country. And this seems to give the lie to what, you know, the traditional notions

00:34:46.640 --> 00:34:52.280
[Amit Varma]: of the constitution that you've referred to as being, as you say, in your book, a series

00:34:52.280 --> 00:34:57.360
[Amit Varma]: of self-interested compromises and arrangements between the Raj and locals, stop quote, as

00:34:57.360 --> 00:35:01.760
[Amit Varma]: if it was just happenstance as if it emerged piecemeal, take this from there, take this

00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:05.800
[Amit Varma]: from there. But, but no, there's actually this sort of unified thinking going on behind

00:35:05.800 --> 00:35:06.800
[Guest]: it.

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:11.440
[Guest]: No, completely. I think that it's both a coherent, cogent project, and it's a radical project.

00:35:11.440 --> 00:35:16.400
[Guest]: And you know, one of the things, Amit, that's been very interesting, right, is look, it's

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:24.560
[Guest]: 2020. It's 70 years of India's constitution. And you only had one book on the founding,

00:35:24.560 --> 00:35:31.800
[Guest]: a book in 1966 by Granville Austin. Now, when I began writing this book, my interest was

00:35:31.800 --> 00:35:36.840
[Guest]: that, look, Granville Austin has done an excellent political history in a straight up way. This

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:41.280
[Guest]: person entered the room, these were the amendments, these were the debates, this was chosen for

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:49.040
[Guest]: ABC reason. But there was very little in Austin's book about the broader intellectual history

00:35:49.040 --> 00:35:55.120
[Guest]: at the level of concepts and ideas and the general terrain of actually what made this

00:35:55.120 --> 00:36:02.640
[Guest]: special in a global way, there was relatively less. Now, I began thinking that, look, there

00:36:02.640 --> 00:36:07.400
[Guest]: must be relatively less because actually there's not that much to say, right? Like the road

00:36:07.400 --> 00:36:13.080
[Guest]: is less traveled for a reason. Sometimes many topics have only one book with good reason.

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:17.620
[Guest]: Actually they should have, most topics should have zero books. And the thing is that I then

00:36:17.620 --> 00:36:23.720
[Guest]: realized that, look, in part what's happened is people have said one of three things. They've

00:36:23.720 --> 00:36:28.560
[Guest]: either said that, look, there's nothing special about this constitution because it's the government

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:34.320
[Guest]: of India Act 1935, which I think is completely wrong. The second thing that some people have

00:36:34.320 --> 00:36:39.120
[Guest]: said is that, look, actually there's nothing special at the level of ideas because it's

00:36:39.120 --> 00:36:44.520
[Guest]: just self-interested people who are just striking bargains, which didn't make sense to me because

00:36:44.520 --> 00:36:48.360
[Guest]: you're going into the assembly and you're granting universal suffrage and the next year

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:54.880
[Guest]: you could be out. So there's clearly something else going on. And I think ideas do matter.

00:36:54.880 --> 00:37:00.640
[Guest]: I think historical events are shaped by a combination of many things, incentives, structures,

00:37:00.640 --> 00:37:05.240
[Guest]: circumstances, ideas, but ideas do matter, right? And that's an assumption in the book

00:37:05.240 --> 00:37:10.520
[Guest]: that actually people do have beliefs. And the third thing is that some people think,

00:37:10.520 --> 00:37:16.320
[Guest]: look, it doesn't matter because India didn't have a revolution at all. Actually, the site

00:37:16.320 --> 00:37:21.840
[Guest]: of revolution is never the political, it's always the social, it's agrarian structures,

00:37:21.840 --> 00:37:29.400
[Guest]: it's economic structures, so on and so forth. And there the implicit contrast is China,

00:37:29.400 --> 00:37:34.040
[Guest]: right? And the thought is that, look, China had a revolution and India didn't. And clearly

00:37:34.040 --> 00:37:38.360
[Guest]: that's not what my people think, right? The people I'm working on and the people I think

00:37:38.360 --> 00:37:43.600
[Guest]: about. And I also don't think that that's true. I think that the constitution did transform

00:37:43.600 --> 00:37:47.960
[Guest]: India. And I think both Nehru understands that and the current government understands

00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:52.720
[Guest]: that. They both want to change the constitution and that you would only change something if

00:37:52.720 --> 00:38:00.480
[Guest]: it matters. Nobody kicks a dead dog. And so I think that when I explored the reasons why

00:38:00.480 --> 00:38:06.160
[Guest]: this had been so understudied, it struck me that there was actually something waiting

00:38:06.160 --> 00:38:11.920
[Guest]: to be written. And what was waiting to be written was exactly what you said, is that

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:19.560
[Guest]: this is a moment where you have to create a democratic citizen through democratic politics.

00:38:19.560 --> 00:38:27.320
[Guest]: In every other country, you have a level of education, social harmony, administrative

00:38:27.320 --> 00:38:36.480
[Guest]: systems increasing, wealth, income rising. And the democratic citizen, which is to say

00:38:36.480 --> 00:38:43.040
[Guest]: the person who behaves in a certain civic way, actually emerges and then you create

00:38:43.040 --> 00:38:47.600
[Guest]: democratic politics. Here we have to create the democratic citizen through democratic

00:38:47.600 --> 00:38:53.360
[Guest]: politics. And how do we do that? What is it? What are the systems that are going to make

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:57.480
[Guest]: people behave in one way rather than another way? That's the question.

00:38:57.480 --> 00:39:02.200
[Amit Varma]: And you have this intriguing sentence in your book where you say, quote, a feature of this

00:39:02.200 --> 00:39:07.040
[Amit Varma]: conception, which is a conception of democracy and the constitution. The feature of this

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:12.560
[Amit Varma]: conception was that popular authorization, that is the exercise of the vote, was necessary

00:39:12.560 --> 00:39:18.280
[Amit Varma]: but insufficient for a political system to have legitimate authority. Stop quote. Can

00:39:18.280 --> 00:39:22.560
[Amit Varma]: you elaborate on, you know, you're saying then to build this democracy, the vote is

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:25.840
[Amit Varma]: necessary but insufficient. What completes the picture?

00:39:25.840 --> 00:39:30.640
[Guest]: Right, absolutely. So I think actually, Amit, this is a really important question today.

00:39:30.640 --> 00:39:34.360
[Guest]: Because one of the things that a lot of people are grappling with today, and I get asked

00:39:34.360 --> 00:39:41.040
[Guest]: this a lot, is look, India is still democratic? Or is it like democracy versus the constitution?

00:39:41.040 --> 00:39:45.600
[Guest]: You know, like in our current protests, you've had a number of people picking up images of

00:39:45.600 --> 00:39:50.160
[Guest]: the constitution, reciting the preamble. And so the question is, is there some clash? And

00:39:50.160 --> 00:39:54.360
[Guest]: I don't think there is a clash, actually. I think that both people are articulating

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:59.200
[Guest]: very distinct visions of democracy. At the heart of the founding is the thought that

00:39:59.200 --> 00:40:06.720
[Guest]: look to be in a democracy means in the first instance that you actually elect those in

00:40:06.720 --> 00:40:12.600
[Guest]: power. But that's not enough. And why is that not enough? Right? Because if that's enough,

00:40:12.600 --> 00:40:16.320
[Guest]: then we don't need to have a constitution at all. We just need one provision which says

00:40:16.320 --> 00:40:21.520
[Guest]: elections every five years, people vote, end of the story, right? And the reason why that's

00:40:21.520 --> 00:40:31.480
[Guest]: not enough is because the question arises, once people vote, and an outcome is generated,

00:40:31.480 --> 00:40:36.960
[Guest]: why should I actually accept that outcome? What gives the state legitimacy? So the state,

00:40:36.960 --> 00:40:43.420
[Guest]: for example, has a certain amount of exclusive legitimacy and a certain amount of authority.

00:40:43.420 --> 00:40:48.360
[Guest]: If the police come to your house and arrest you, as opposed to some goons, you think that

00:40:48.360 --> 00:40:52.440
[Guest]: the police speak with a different kind of moral and legal authority. Now the question

00:40:52.440 --> 00:40:58.160
[Guest]: is what gives them that? And the answer is that what gives them that is that firstly,

00:40:58.160 --> 00:41:02.880
[Guest]: we believe that they have been put in place through a certain process, right? So we have

00:41:02.880 --> 00:41:07.680
[Guest]: elected people in power who are governing the police. But the second is at the level

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:14.040
[Guest]: of outcomes that those systems are actually treating people as free and equal beings.

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:18.960
[Guest]: Because if they are not, I have no reason to accept it. The state cannot claim moral

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:25.160
[Guest]: authority over me unless it treats me equally. And so the whole question in the Constituent

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:30.440
[Guest]: Assembly is, I'm going to create a state, I'm going to create authority, and I've had

00:41:30.440 --> 00:41:36.800
[Guest]: illegitimate authority for 200 years. And what would it mean to actually create a system

00:41:36.800 --> 00:41:42.800
[Guest]: that not only grants the right to vote, but can justify the authority of the state that

00:41:42.800 --> 00:41:48.760
[Guest]: can actually treat people as free and equal beings? What would the meaning of that be?

00:41:48.760 --> 00:41:56.460
[Guest]: And the whole constitution in some ways is an effort to work out that notion, right?

00:41:56.460 --> 00:42:02.600
[Guest]: What are the structures of power that would make people behave in certain ways, such that

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:07.880
[Amit Varma]: the outcomes generated would be free and equal? So this sort of brings up a question which

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:12.720
[Amit Varma]: arises later in your book, but I'll ask it now about the clash between these two schools

00:42:12.720 --> 00:42:17.480
[Amit Varma]: of thought and constitutionalism, that is legal constitutionalism and political constitutionalism.

00:42:17.480 --> 00:42:22.920
[Amit Varma]: The legal constitutionalists believe that the key job of the Constitution is to lay

00:42:22.920 --> 00:42:27.240
[Amit Varma]: down rules of the game and act as a restraint on power, and to make sure that the state

00:42:27.240 --> 00:42:32.000
[Amit Varma]: does not overstep its limits and that it protects the individual rights of its citizens. Whereas

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:37.160
[Amit Varma]: political constitutionalism holds a view that no, the state must do more than that. And

00:42:37.160 --> 00:42:43.160
[Amit Varma]: the state must actually change or improve society as it were, depending on where you

00:42:43.160 --> 00:42:48.760
[Amit Varma]: want to run with that. And this was also a fundamental clash at the founding. And there

00:42:48.760 --> 00:42:52.680
[Amit Varma]: were people who argued for both. And there are people who still today could say that

00:42:52.680 --> 00:42:57.040
[Amit Varma]: we have one or the other. Can you take me a bit through the sort of debates on this?

00:42:57.040 --> 00:43:02.160
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, the way I think slightly different to how you describe it only in the following

00:43:02.160 --> 00:43:07.960
[Guest]: way that people who want this, some people see the Constitution as merely an articulation

00:43:07.960 --> 00:43:12.680
[Guest]: of democracy, right? That it's just about voting. And some people see it as something

00:43:12.680 --> 00:43:17.900
[Guest]: much thicker, right? It grants you many more rights, it grants you many more freedoms.

00:43:17.900 --> 00:43:24.040
[Guest]: And so there's a kind of limit on the democratic process in some sense. And I think the way

00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:28.080
[Guest]: I frame it and the way they frame it is they say, look, what both of these debates have

00:43:28.080 --> 00:43:33.720
[Guest]: presumed is they've already presumed a kind of democratic citizen, right? And actually

00:43:33.720 --> 00:43:39.000
[Guest]: even to exercise the vote, the reason why we think certain constitutional principles

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:44.560
[Guest]: are important is because we think that that is actually essential to democracy itself.

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:50.640
[Guest]: So let's play it in a very simple and tangible way. For example, assume that you think, look,

00:43:50.640 --> 00:43:55.120
[Guest]: the current government is justified in everything because it has been voted into power. Okay.

00:43:55.120 --> 00:43:59.600
[Guest]: And that would be true for any government. Let's just say you take that view, right?

00:43:59.600 --> 00:44:04.960
[Guest]: Then the question arises, okay, if that's true, what does that entail? That entails

00:44:04.960 --> 00:44:10.760
[Guest]: that firstly, if it's everybody has the right to vote, okay. That means that you need to

00:44:10.760 --> 00:44:16.600
[Guest]: have a system where actually votes are counted fairly. Yes. That means that you actually

00:44:16.600 --> 00:44:22.160
[Guest]: have to have also a system where people can campaign equally freely. Yes. That means that

00:44:22.160 --> 00:44:27.200
[Guest]: people, you should also say, if you care only about voting and only about those processes,

00:44:27.200 --> 00:44:31.720
[Guest]: that people have to be able to deliberate during the process because then they can only

00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:35.840
[Guest]: then they can vote freely. They have to be able to read and write. They have to be able

00:44:35.840 --> 00:44:40.920
[Guest]: to think about the choices they are making. If you do all those things, you get a lot

00:44:40.920 --> 00:44:48.160
[Guest]: of freedoms anyway. And then the question arises, okay, the government is legitimate

00:44:48.160 --> 00:44:54.600
[Guest]: because it is voted in. Is it then legitimate for it to say that X group of the population

00:44:54.600 --> 00:44:59.120
[Guest]: are no longer on the voter list? You could say, no, that may not be right because it

00:44:59.120 --> 00:45:03.680
[Guest]: needs to still preserve the process of voting in, right? So it needs, it can't disenfranchise

00:45:03.680 --> 00:45:07.640
[Guest]: anybody, right? But the question is, okay, if it can't disenfranchise, what else can

00:45:07.640 --> 00:45:12.720
[Guest]: it not do? Can it stop them from talking? Can it arrest them without? So a lot you can

00:45:12.720 --> 00:45:19.800
[Guest]: get in by just realizing that even to express sovereignty, you need certain rights and conditions.

00:45:19.800 --> 00:45:25.240
[Guest]: And the problem with the Indian founding is those rights and conditions and that knowledge

00:45:25.240 --> 00:45:29.920
[Guest]: and understanding doesn't exist in Indian society, right? The ultimate thing is that

00:45:29.920 --> 00:45:35.960
[Guest]: you think when people vote in a genuinely democratic society, they are thinking about

00:45:35.960 --> 00:45:40.280
[Guest]: the common good. They are thinking about the collective good. They are not seeing you as

00:45:40.280 --> 00:45:47.120
[Guest]: belonging to X village, Y caste, C religion. They are actually seeing you as citizens.

00:45:47.120 --> 00:45:51.040
[Guest]: That's what it means to have a democratic sensibility, right? That you actually become

00:45:51.040 --> 00:45:56.000
[Guest]: a different kind of person in how you see the other person. And the question in India's

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:04.280
[Guest]: constitutional founding is what kind of apparatus, what kind of computer program can I put the

00:46:04.280 --> 00:46:11.240
[Guest]: people in that they begin to see other people like that? What system will change that? Because

00:46:11.240 --> 00:46:16.080
[Guest]: in our current politics, they only see people like that, current politics at that time,

00:46:16.080 --> 00:46:20.480
[Guest]: and that cannot enable democracy, because that cannot enable a common good and that

00:46:20.480 --> 00:46:23.440
[Guest]: cannot enable a sustainable political environment.

00:46:23.440 --> 00:46:28.880
[Amit Varma]: So what you're saying is that even if the argument for legal constitutionalism were

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:33.960
[Amit Varma]: to be true, that a government should exist only to protect the rights of democratic citizens

00:46:33.960 --> 00:46:39.120
[Amit Varma]: and not actually try to reshape society, the argument cannot hold unless you actually have

00:46:39.120 --> 00:46:44.400
[Unknown]: democratic citizens and a democratic society. Absolutely. That's a precondition. Absolutely.

00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:48.520
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the constitution has to venture beyond mere legal constitutionalism.

00:46:48.520 --> 00:46:53.480
[Guest]: Completely. I mean, a lot of the debates in the West are debates that have already presumed

00:46:53.480 --> 00:46:58.360
[Guest]: a certain level of society, right? I mean, you see this, for example, even in our debates

00:46:58.360 --> 00:47:04.960
[Guest]: in the West around things like hate speech, right? You may say, oh, if I have a perfectly

00:47:04.960 --> 00:47:09.600
[Guest]: ordered society, you know, is it okay to let people abuse one another? I mean, the question

00:47:09.600 --> 00:47:13.760
[Guest]: is, how do you get a perfectly ordered society? That's the puzzle, right?

00:47:13.760 --> 00:47:18.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. Let's sort of talk about now, you know, you've got three chapters, and you're looking

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:24.400
[Amit Varma]: at three thematic ways in which there were ideological arguments about what the constitution

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:29.800
[Amit Varma]: should be like. And the first argument is about codification. Now, obviously, we have

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:35.280
[Amit Varma]: everyone knows the longest constitution in the world, it is an unwieldy beast, you know,

00:47:35.280 --> 00:47:39.780
[Amit Varma]: you can fit the American Constitution into the pocket of your shirt. But you cannot really

00:47:39.780 --> 00:47:44.800
[Amit Varma]: do that with the Indian Constitution, unless you have some pretty mighty pecs. And this

00:47:44.800 --> 00:47:49.680
[Amit Varma]: is not something that sort of, like, as some may presume happened by default, that everybody

00:47:49.680 --> 00:47:53.080
[Amit Varma]: just put in whatever they wanted, and you ended up with something really long. This

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:56.480
[Amit Varma]: was deliberate, there was a reasoning for this, there was a debate behind this, tell

00:47:56.480 --> 00:47:57.480
[Amit Varma]: me a bit about that.

00:47:57.480 --> 00:48:01.840
[Guest]: And no, so I think, I think you're absolutely right. I mean, my you know, years ago, I wrote

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:07.040
[Guest]: a short introduction to the Indian Constitution, which I think is shorter than the document.

00:48:07.040 --> 00:48:12.480
[Guest]: Okay, right. And so somebody suggested to me, oh, you should have an appendix to the

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:16.160
[Guest]: book with the constitution as like, you have no idea, like, it's going to be double the

00:48:16.160 --> 00:48:21.840
[Guest]: length, right? The constitution is long, it is unwieldy. And the question, the most elementary

00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:27.680
[Guest]: question to ask is, why is all this stuff there? Right? Actually, why is why are all

00:48:27.680 --> 00:48:33.840
[Guest]: these things in the constitution, when you other constitutions don't have them. And the

00:48:33.840 --> 00:48:40.080
[Guest]: most easy way I meant to think about this or to understand it is that in other countries,

00:48:40.080 --> 00:48:47.680
[Guest]: all of those norms are already a given. Whereas in this constitution, you are operating under

00:48:47.680 --> 00:48:55.480
[Guest]: the fear of profound uncertainty. After popular authorization, the question is that you suddenly

00:48:55.480 --> 00:49:04.320
[Guest]: are going to have voters, judges, legislatures, members of the executive, all now operating

00:49:04.320 --> 00:49:10.480
[Guest]: under conditions of popular authorization. And you have absolutely no idea how they will

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:16.720
[Guest]: behave. And the key thing is, they don't know how to behave. And so codification is an attempt

00:49:16.720 --> 00:49:24.320
[Guest]: to actually explain and develop the meaning of certain rights or certain responsibilities

00:49:24.320 --> 00:49:30.560
[Guest]: or certain rules. It's to add texture, because nothing can be given. I mean, the way to think

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:35.600
[Guest]: about it is that suddenly you're putting some people in a room, and you're asking them to

00:49:35.600 --> 00:49:40.560
[Guest]: speak a new language. What is the first thing you have to do, you have to give them a very

00:49:40.560 --> 00:49:45.920
[Guest]: long lecture on grammar. And that is basically what codification is trying to do. It is an

00:49:45.920 --> 00:49:52.160
[Guest]: elaboration of the grammar of democracy and constitutionalism, because that doesn't exist

00:49:52.160 --> 00:49:54.880
[Guest]: in India. And so I need to put all that in the document.

00:49:54.880 --> 00:50:00.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And there were objections raised at the time that, look, a lot of these things

00:50:00.400 --> 00:50:04.680
[Amit Varma]: that you're detailing out are things that legislators should do, or that the executive

00:50:04.680 --> 00:50:09.240
[Amit Varma]: should do or whatever. Why are you, you know, laying these rules out there? And the counter

00:50:09.240 --> 00:50:14.920
[Amit Varma]: argument was that, look, there is no established practice of doing all of these things either

00:50:14.920 --> 00:50:20.120
[Amit Varma]: in the legislature or the judiciary or whatever. So you want to lay out as many details as

00:50:20.120 --> 00:50:22.680
[Amit Varma]: possible. That's broadly the sort of thing.

00:50:22.680 --> 00:50:28.040
[Guest]: That's broadly the thing. And I think that sense is also that, look, in previous countries,

00:50:28.040 --> 00:50:31.960
[Guest]: legislatures and executive have done it already with certain preconceived ideas, right? I

00:50:31.960 --> 00:50:36.280
[Guest]: mean, there were some attempts in the Constituent Assembly to think you're actually limiting

00:50:36.280 --> 00:50:41.160
[Guest]: future legislators or none of that I think is actually true. I think you're just making

00:50:41.160 --> 00:50:46.080
[Guest]: explicit what a society lacks as being implicit.

00:50:46.080 --> 00:50:51.400
[Amit Varma]: And there was criticism even at the time that it was just increasing the coercive power

00:50:51.400 --> 00:50:57.420
[Amit Varma]: of the state. And for example, Somnath Lahiri said, quote, none of the existing provisions

00:50:57.420 --> 00:51:01.480
[Amit Varma]: of the powers of the executive have been done away with. Rather, in some respects, those

00:51:01.480 --> 00:51:05.960
[Amit Varma]: powers are sought to be increased, stop quote. And he later said something to the effect

00:51:05.960 --> 00:51:09.640
[Amit Varma]: of how the constitution looks like it has been written for a police constable at that

00:51:09.640 --> 00:51:10.640
[Guest]: level of detail.

00:51:10.640 --> 00:51:16.040
[Guest]: Absolutely. There are two things, right? One is there are criticisms across the board,

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:20.520
[Guest]: right? And that's one of the fascinating things about the Constituent Assembly debates, right?

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:24.480
[Guest]: If you read the Constituent Assembly debates, there's a lot of random stuff going on. But

00:51:24.480 --> 00:51:30.360
[Guest]: what's heartening is the amount of intellectual diversity. Now, the specific part that you

00:51:30.360 --> 00:51:36.280
[Guest]: just read out was a part negotiating a very peculiar feature in the constitution, which

00:51:36.280 --> 00:51:41.760
[Guest]: I think a lot of us are familiar with, is that certain rights are recognized, say the

00:51:41.760 --> 00:51:47.000
[Guest]: right to free speech. And then there are certain exceptions listed. And one of the things that

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:51.400
[Guest]: was said at the assembly and is often even said today is that, look, what is the meaning

00:51:51.400 --> 00:51:55.200
[Guest]: of this? You're giving the right and then you're giving these exceptions. Now, what

00:51:55.200 --> 00:52:00.520
[Guest]: was the answer in the assembly? The answer in the assembly was, look, this right has

00:52:00.520 --> 00:52:06.800
[Guest]: been limited in every country. We are not doing anything new. Even in America, which is massively

00:52:06.800 --> 00:52:11.440
[Guest]: invested in free speech, there are limitations. You have two options available. Either you

00:52:11.440 --> 00:52:17.280
[Guest]: recognize the right and then you leave the limitations to legislators or the judiciary,

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:22.720
[Guest]: or you actually agree on certain established principle limitations and you just put them

00:52:22.720 --> 00:52:28.080
[Guest]: in now. And what that does is that doesn't limit the right. If anything, it might even

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:32.880
[Guest]: limit the limitations because you can then say that, look, you can actually only limit

00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:37.680
[Guest]: it on these particular grounds, right? If you leave it open tomorrow, parliament or

00:52:37.680 --> 00:52:43.600
[Guest]: the judiciary could impose 10 other limitations. So it's the codification exercises, neither

00:52:43.600 --> 00:52:49.680
[Guest]: increasing nor decreasing state power. It's just explaining to you what free speech is.

00:52:49.680 --> 00:52:54.380
[Guest]: And so their point is, look, free speech is meaningless if you just don't provide any

00:52:54.380 --> 00:53:00.800
[Guest]: limitation or contours or boundaries or understanding of it. And if you have those that are established

00:53:00.800 --> 00:53:06.200
[Guest]: and if we can agree on them, let's just do them now. Because actually, otherwise you

00:53:06.200 --> 00:53:13.040
[Guest]: leave it to 50 years of litigation. And one of the things that they do, right, is they

00:53:13.040 --> 00:53:17.360
[Guest]: on this issue, they engage hugely with American law at the time. And they said, look, if you

00:53:17.360 --> 00:53:23.000
[Guest]: see American cases over the last 50 years, over the last 20 years, 30 years, they have

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:28.840
[Guest]: constantly changed their minds. And if you can't trust a judiciary that has so much experience

00:53:28.840 --> 00:53:33.200
[Guest]: in common law reasoning, what are you going to trust ours? And so there's this fear of

00:53:33.200 --> 00:53:38.440
[Guest]: uncertainty and the sense is that, look, let's just put it in. And the idea actually, Amit,

00:53:38.440 --> 00:53:43.240
[Guest]: that look, the fact that there are limitations can also strengthen the right. It just turns

00:53:43.240 --> 00:53:50.440
[Guest]: on application is not some fanciful idea just by me. So a few years ago, one of the most

00:53:50.440 --> 00:53:55.400
[Guest]: important and one of the rare decisions of the Indian Supreme Court that really upheld

00:53:55.400 --> 00:54:01.640
[Guest]: free speech was a decision about section 66A of the Information Technology Act, which you

00:54:01.640 --> 00:54:08.080
[Guest]: might be familiar with, which had very wide provisions relating to, you know, WhatsAppping,

00:54:08.080 --> 00:54:12.560
[Guest]: email communication, so on and so forth. And there were issues about its constitutionality

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:18.500
[Guest]: and it was struck down. And in the judgment, Justice Rohit Nariman gave an outstanding

00:54:18.500 --> 00:54:23.800
[Guest]: judgment where basically what he said is he said, look, if this law is valid, it has to

00:54:23.800 --> 00:54:28.360
[Guest]: be valid under these specific limitations. There's no other limitation. So that's an

00:54:28.360 --> 00:54:32.760
[Guest]: example where having limitations also limits the grounds on which you can limit.

00:54:32.760 --> 00:54:39.000
[Amit Varma]: I think it's a very clever and cogent argument that by listing out the limitations, you are

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:42.480
[Amit Varma]: actually putting a limit on the limitations and therefore you're increasing freedom and

00:54:42.480 --> 00:54:46.320
[Guest]: not decreasing it. I mean, what I want to say is that you're neither increasing nor

00:54:46.320 --> 00:54:50.960
[Guest]: decreasing. For them, they are saying, look, to guarantee a right without telling you what

00:54:50.960 --> 00:54:55.680
[Amit Varma]: the right is, is to guarantee nothing. Yeah, but you know, I find that a bit tenuous

00:54:55.680 --> 00:55:01.200
[Amit Varma]: because just looking at the restrictions include things like public order, morality and decency

00:55:01.200 --> 00:55:07.200
[Amit Varma]: and all of those which are open to interpretation and will inevitably therefore be interpreted

00:55:07.200 --> 00:55:12.440
[Amit Varma]: by the state and by the judiciary, which it seems is now captured by the state. And the

00:55:12.440 --> 00:55:18.000
[Amit Varma]: second implication of, say, not having something that is as absolute in the support of free

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:23.600
[Amit Varma]: speech as, say, the US First Amendment, is that we still have various laws from the Indian

00:55:23.600 --> 00:55:30.360
[Amit Varma]: Penal Code on our book, like 295A, 153A and indeed the sedition law, which is being massively

00:55:30.360 --> 00:55:35.080
[Amit Varma]: misused by this current administration and children and entire villages are being booked

00:55:35.080 --> 00:55:40.120
[Amit Varma]: under sedition, which really should not exist. But I presume they exist because the Constitution

00:55:40.120 --> 00:55:47.320
[Guest]: allows these limitations. So firstly, I completely share your horror at the application of free

00:55:47.320 --> 00:55:52.360
[Guest]: speech in India, right? I think it's a mistake to say that that's because the Constitution

00:55:52.360 --> 00:55:56.960
[Guest]: allows it. I think that the Constitution actually doesn't allow it. I think it's pure, it's

00:55:56.960 --> 00:56:02.080
[Guest]: very poorly applied. I think it's misapplied. And I think that there's very little that

00:56:02.080 --> 00:56:06.920
[Amit Varma]: the Constitution can do about that. It's very, these restrictions, you will agree with me

00:56:06.920 --> 00:56:11.960
[Amit Varma]: surely are very vaguely worded in terms of public order, decency and morality. These

00:56:11.960 --> 00:56:16.160
[Guest]: are open to interpretation. I mean, they are open to interpretation, but because something

00:56:16.160 --> 00:56:20.680
[Guest]: is open to interpretation doesn't mean that it's interpreted correctly. Right? And that

00:56:20.680 --> 00:56:24.680
[Amit Varma]: itself is open to interpretation. We can go round in circles. No, we can. But then the

00:56:24.680 --> 00:56:29.240
[Guest]: idea is that the rules should be so specific that... But I don't think any rule can be

00:56:29.240 --> 00:56:34.800
[Guest]: so specific. I mean, at the ultimate analysis, all of constitutional law and indeed all of

00:56:34.800 --> 00:56:42.040
[Guest]: law is forged in practice. Right? Or I mean, if you could frame things with complete clarity,

00:56:42.040 --> 00:56:46.680
[Guest]: you would not have problems of interpretation in anything. In the books you read, in the

00:56:46.680 --> 00:56:52.880
[Guest]: music you hear, in the movies you watch, people disagree on what something means all the time.

00:56:52.880 --> 00:56:57.120
[Guest]: But you have canons of interpretation. And you're absolutely right that these exceptions

00:56:57.120 --> 00:57:02.880
[Guest]: have given the state much more presumptive power than any of us would like. I don't think

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:07.040
[Guest]: that that was the constitutional vision. I think that what's happened is that you've

00:57:07.040 --> 00:57:12.960
[Guest]: actually had exceptions and you've interpreted them in a way to swallow up the right. And

00:57:12.960 --> 00:57:19.960
[Guest]: so I'm not at all on board with that. But I think that it's a mistake to conflate general

00:57:19.960 --> 00:57:26.120
[Guest]: rules and rules by definition have to be general with how they are applied. Right? And I think

00:57:26.120 --> 00:57:34.360
[Guest]: that we should also be very reluctant to actually criticize the Constitution for current moments

00:57:34.360 --> 00:57:40.400
[Guest]: in Indian politics, as well as to praise it. Ultimately, constitutional success or failure

00:57:40.400 --> 00:57:48.080
[Guest]: rests on a certain kind of political consensus external to the Constitution. If you have

00:57:48.080 --> 00:57:52.940
[Guest]: a political and judicial consensus that doesn't want to recognize free speech, no provision

00:57:52.940 --> 00:57:57.840
[Guest]: is going to be able to save you. And so the thing is that the Constitution is providing

00:57:57.840 --> 00:58:02.160
[Guest]: what? It's like almost you have a fridge that is providing you some mechanism on how to

00:58:02.160 --> 00:58:08.040
[Guest]: cool food. If you don't want to plug the fridge in, it's not the fridge's fault. Right? And

00:58:08.040 --> 00:58:15.280
[Guest]: so at the founding, you actually have a document that they put in place to create a certain

00:58:15.280 --> 00:58:20.800
[Guest]: kind of citizen. And you have a political consensus on interpreting that document in

00:58:20.800 --> 00:58:26.520
[Guest]: a certain way and taking that document seriously. Right? If either of those go, you're not going

00:58:26.520 --> 00:58:33.400
[Guest]: to get that citizen. Right? I mean, part of what you see in India today is a certain manipulation

00:58:33.400 --> 00:58:39.560
[Guest]: of the Constitution, but also a certain attempt in some quarters to disregard it altogether.

00:58:39.560 --> 00:58:45.360
[Guest]: Extra constitutional violence, right? Extra constitutional actions. And so that's not

00:58:45.360 --> 00:58:50.680
[Guest]: even to take it seriously. Now, in that the Constitution can only do so much, right? You're

00:58:50.680 --> 00:58:55.480
[Guest]: going to have to have that kind of the political elite and the judicial elite have to buy into

00:58:55.480 --> 00:58:56.480
[Guest]: the document.

00:58:56.480 --> 00:59:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So, I recorded with Kapil Komireddy last week, and we were talking about his book Malevolent

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:07.200
[Amit Varma]: Republic. And we spoke about your book a bit and it was exactly on sort of this point where

00:59:07.200 --> 00:59:12.960
[Amit Varma]: he argued that the conception is not flawed, but the execution is. And my argument was

00:59:12.960 --> 00:59:19.240
[Amit Varma]: that the execution is flawed because the conception is. It is because of these vaguely worded

00:59:19.240 --> 00:59:24.960
[Amit Varma]: restrictions that the application of the law can be so open and so can go in all these

00:59:24.960 --> 00:59:28.480
[Amit Varma]: different directions. And for what it's worth, this is not a criticism I'm making with regard

00:59:28.480 --> 00:59:33.400
[Amit Varma]: to current events. I have written columns 15 years ago, we're arguing about these exact

00:59:33.400 --> 00:59:38.040
[Amit Varma]: same laws and the Congress has misused them as much. And if you look at the US First Amendment,

00:59:38.040 --> 00:59:44.440
[Amit Varma]: they don't have these caveats and therefore they don't have such blatant misuses of, you

00:59:44.440 --> 00:59:45.520
[Guest]: know, free speech laws.

00:59:45.520 --> 00:59:49.400
[Guest]: But they have plenty of caveats that have been introduced by the judiciary. They don't

00:59:49.400 --> 00:59:54.560
[Guest]: have free speech laws because the judiciary is not allowed them. Ours has. Why is sedition

00:59:54.560 --> 00:59:58.440
[Guest]: not been struck down? Why is criminal defamation been upheld?

00:59:58.440 --> 00:59:59.440
[Amit Varma]: Why?

00:59:59.440 --> 01:00:03.480
[Guest]: Because the judiciary has a very different interpretation of free speech. I mean, all

01:00:03.480 --> 01:00:08.280
[Guest]: of those laws have no place either under the Constitution. If you say that the exception

01:00:08.280 --> 01:00:10.800
[Guest]: means more than the right, what can I say to you?

01:00:10.800 --> 01:00:16.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, fair enough. Let's kind of move on. I mean, your chapter on codification after

01:00:16.480 --> 01:00:21.260
[Amit Varma]: giving you know, this absolutely fascinating laying out this fascinating debate about should

01:00:21.260 --> 01:00:26.960
[Amit Varma]: we have a thick constitution or a thin one and you've even quoted Nehru, you know, talking

01:00:26.960 --> 01:00:31.160
[Amit Varma]: in detail about why we don't need a thick constitution and blah, blah, blah. And then

01:00:31.160 --> 01:00:38.040
[Amit Varma]: Ambedkar very eloquently pointing out, and I'll quote him on this quote, constitutional

01:00:38.040 --> 01:00:43.120
[Amit Varma]: morality is not a natural sentiment. It has to be cultivated. We must realize that our

01:00:43.120 --> 01:00:48.560
[Amit Varma]: people have yet to learn it. Democracy in India is only a top dressing on an Indian

01:00:48.560 --> 01:00:54.120
[Amit Varma]: soil, which is essentially undemocratic. Stop code and we can make of that what we will.

01:00:54.120 --> 01:01:00.360
[Amit Varma]: So you have sort of three sort of illustrations of this codification in this chapter. And

01:01:00.360 --> 01:01:05.040
[Amit Varma]: the second one is what we just kind of spoke about where rights and their caveats, which

01:01:05.040 --> 01:01:09.440
[Amit Varma]: were hotly debated, because many felt like Somnath Lahiri and other legislators that

01:01:09.440 --> 01:01:13.520
[Amit Varma]: there should be no caveats. Otherwise, what is the point? And I must say, I tend to agree

01:01:13.520 --> 01:01:18.280
[Amit Varma]: with that. But I understand the reasoning behind it. It's extremely cogent, and it's

01:01:18.280 --> 01:01:24.800
[Amit Varma]: just a statist instinct somehow rationalizing itself. Another example you gave is of the

01:01:24.800 --> 01:01:29.840
[Amit Varma]: directive principles. Tell me a bit about you know, those specific debates that you've

01:01:29.840 --> 01:01:35.720
[Amit Varma]: got those directive principles in the constitution, they are not enforceable. So it is almost

01:01:35.720 --> 01:01:39.560
[Amit Varma]: like a lecture that they have virtue signaling earlier, but if they're not enforceable, why

01:01:39.560 --> 01:01:43.800
[Guest]: are they there at all? So this was one view, right? And so there have been two puzzles

01:01:43.800 --> 01:01:49.640
[Guest]: about the directive principles. One puzzle has been exactly the one you said that look,

01:01:49.640 --> 01:01:55.080
[Guest]: if they are not enforceable, what are they doing there? And the second puzzle is the

01:01:55.080 --> 01:02:02.400
[Guest]: puzzle that look earlier they used to be enforceable in previous documents. Why was that a switch?

01:02:02.400 --> 01:02:07.640
[Guest]: I think that there's an answer to both things. Let's begin with the second question first,

01:02:07.640 --> 01:02:11.160
[Guest]: which is I don't think there was a switch. That's the first thing I want to say. And

01:02:11.160 --> 01:02:16.320
[Guest]: I think that this is one issue on which Nija Jayal and I have a disagreement. And so one

01:02:16.320 --> 01:02:22.880
[Guest]: of the things that she mentioned in her extraordinary book is how Ambedkar actually shifted his

01:02:22.880 --> 01:02:30.640
[Guest]: view from a memorandum to a subsequent speech. I spent some time discussing Ambedkar and

01:02:30.640 --> 01:02:37.320
[Guest]: I don't think he switched his view. So I actually think that the view was consistent all along.

01:02:37.320 --> 01:02:43.480
[Guest]: And the view was that any legitimate state needs to be committed to both civil liberties

01:02:43.480 --> 01:02:48.840
[Guest]: and it needs to be committed to social and economic welfare. That never changed previously

01:02:48.840 --> 01:02:55.640
[Guest]: and it didn't change later. Now the question is, why are they there if they cannot be enforced?

01:02:55.640 --> 01:03:00.000
[Guest]: And I think there are two, three things going on here. I think the first is the sense that

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:10.720
[Guest]: look, judicial enforcement is actually a question of specific institutional design, right? Whether

01:03:10.720 --> 01:03:19.400
[Guest]: or not something is judicially enforced is not necessarily signifying its importance.

01:03:19.400 --> 01:03:24.440
[Guest]: It is actually signifying something else, that this is something that is fit for determination

01:03:24.440 --> 01:03:30.440
[Guest]: by the judiciary and it is a matter of law enforcement, right? Because the legislature

01:03:30.440 --> 01:03:37.120
[Guest]: makes laws, executive applies laws, judicially enforces laws, right? Now, part of what's

01:03:37.120 --> 01:03:43.040
[Guest]: happening in that moment is that countries are only recognizing civil political rights

01:03:43.040 --> 01:03:50.000
[Guest]: and some are not even, like the Soviet Union, right? What the director principles do is

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:54.480
[Guest]: the combination of civil political rights and socioeconomic goals, the fundamental rights

01:03:54.480 --> 01:03:59.960
[Guest]: and the director principles means that the constitution is providing both the means by

01:03:59.960 --> 01:04:05.440
[Guest]: which change can occur, which is through civil liberties, and it's also providing the ends,

01:04:05.440 --> 01:04:11.040
[Guest]: right? Which is a certain amount of economic and social welfare. And the reason they exist

01:04:11.040 --> 01:04:15.360
[Guest]: is that they say, look, in India, because there's no knowledge and understanding, those

01:04:15.360 --> 01:04:21.480
[Guest]: ends might not be clear. You might actually not know that that's the job of government.

01:04:21.480 --> 01:04:25.600
[Guest]: And then Ambedkar asks, what will the security be? And he answers by saying, look, the security

01:04:25.600 --> 01:04:29.600
[Guest]: will be that people will vote each other out, right? Because that's what it means to be

01:04:29.600 --> 01:04:33.760
[Guest]: a democracy. But at least I need to tell people this is what they should be voting on.

01:04:33.760 --> 01:04:37.040
[Amit Varma]: So even if there's no judicial enforcement, there is electoral enforcement.

01:04:37.040 --> 01:04:42.800
[Guest]: Of course, and the point is also to give you a sense of why the civil political liberties

01:04:42.800 --> 01:04:48.080
[Guest]: thing is important as means is, you know, for years, people have gone on and on about

01:04:48.080 --> 01:04:53.280
[Guest]: how socioeconomic rights should be enforced. And now the Indian Supreme Court has often

01:04:53.280 --> 01:05:00.640
[Guest]: done it. Look at where that's gotten you. A tangible example that captures things is

01:05:00.640 --> 01:05:08.080
[Guest]: the Aadhaar judgment. In the Aadhaar judgment, the court is remarkably unconcerned with civil

01:05:08.080 --> 01:05:13.360
[Guest]: political rights on the promise of social and economic welfare, on the development needs

01:05:13.360 --> 01:05:20.520
[Guest]: of India. This is Soviet Union 2.0 in terms of logic, right? And so actually, the enforcement

01:05:20.520 --> 01:05:26.960
[Guest]: of that has got you in a place where the means no longer matter. And so the bifurcation was

01:05:26.960 --> 01:05:31.360
[Guest]: rested on something very significant. It rested on the point that, look, these are certain

01:05:31.360 --> 01:05:35.720
[Guest]: things that are fit for this kind of person. These are certain things that are fit for

01:05:35.720 --> 01:05:40.400
[Guest]: another kind of person. It doesn't mean that one is more important than the other. A country

01:05:40.400 --> 01:05:45.400
[Guest]: may need podcasts and it may need television channels. Doesn't mean that if I don't put

01:05:45.400 --> 01:05:50.280
[Guest]: Amit on TV, I don't think podcasts are important, right? I don't think TV is important. People

01:05:50.280 --> 01:05:55.240
[Guest]: might be suited to very specific things. Institutions are suited to specific things and each have

01:05:55.240 --> 01:06:01.680
[Amit Varma]: their own logic for enforcement and accountability. So if I may sort of frame it this way, you

01:06:01.680 --> 01:06:05.360
[Amit Varma]: have negative rights and positive rights, right? Negative rights come from the whole

01:06:05.360 --> 01:06:10.080
[Amit Varma]: Lockean notion of what people may not do to you. They may not kill you. They may not shut

01:06:10.080 --> 01:06:13.840
[Amit Varma]: you up. So the right to life, the right to free speech, all of those are negative rights

01:06:13.840 --> 01:06:19.120
[Amit Varma]: and all of those are embodied in the fundamental rights, which are judicially enforceable.

01:06:19.120 --> 01:06:25.600
[Amit Varma]: So through that, the state is essentially committing to protecting each individual citizen.

01:06:25.600 --> 01:06:29.480
[Amit Varma]: And positive rights are, I wouldn't even call them rights, I'd call them entitlements, but

01:06:29.480 --> 01:06:32.800
[Amit Varma]: whatever language you use, positive rights are things like the right to education, the

01:06:32.800 --> 01:06:38.120
[Amit Varma]: right to food. And you can only essentially fulfill those rights with a certain amount

01:06:38.120 --> 01:06:42.160
[Amit Varma]: of state coercion, because you need resources to get those, you are infringing negative

01:06:42.160 --> 01:06:46.360
[Amit Varma]: rights somewhere or the other to enforce those. And the decision that the framers therefore

01:06:46.360 --> 01:06:51.920
[Amit Varma]: took was that let's put all the negative rights in the fundamental rights, so people are assured

01:06:51.920 --> 01:06:57.080
[Amit Varma]: that the state will protect them. But there's no point putting the positive rights there

01:06:57.080 --> 01:07:02.080
[Amit Varma]: because society hasn't evolved enough. And let's put them in the directive principles

01:07:02.080 --> 01:07:07.320
[Amit Varma]: so they are clearly stated and enunciated, but we can't make them enforceable. And if

01:07:07.320 --> 01:07:11.960
[Amit Varma]: they are enforceable, it should never be at the cost of the fundamental rights. Is that

01:07:11.960 --> 01:07:19.920
[Guest]: a correct summation? In a way, I mean, I wouldn't exactly frame it like this. Because I think

01:07:19.920 --> 01:07:25.680
[Guest]: that there's been a lot of excellent literature in the last two decades, about how this negative

01:07:25.680 --> 01:07:32.720
[Guest]: positive distinction doesn't fully work. Right? Because at the end of the day, even to support

01:07:32.720 --> 01:07:38.240
[Guest]: negative rights, the state needs to do a lot of positive work. I think the way to think

01:07:38.240 --> 01:07:45.040
[Guest]: about it would be civil political versus socioeconomic. And I think understanding that in the case

01:07:45.040 --> 01:07:52.320
[Guest]: of civil political, we actually refer to individualized remedies, we refer to applications relating

01:07:52.320 --> 01:07:59.160
[Guest]: to a particular specific act, a particular instance, a particular person, a particular

01:07:59.160 --> 01:08:04.480
[Guest]: group of people. In the case of social and economic welfare, we are often framing policy

01:08:04.480 --> 01:08:09.760
[Guest]: questions of a very different kind. But it's more the distinction between civil political

01:08:09.760 --> 01:08:14.840
[Guest]: and socioeconomic than negative positive, because the negative positive just becomes

01:08:14.840 --> 01:08:20.440
[Guest]: tricky, right? Because even if I have to protect, say, the right to free speech, or from arbitrary

01:08:20.440 --> 01:08:25.040
[Guest]: arrest, I still need to have a judicial system to guarantee that I need to have a law enforcement,

01:08:25.040 --> 01:08:28.800
[Guest]: I mean, I still had to do a lot of positive work, nothing is guaranteed by itself.

01:08:28.800 --> 01:08:32.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that's understood. That is the liberal paradox that for your rights to be protected,

01:08:32.840 --> 01:08:36.520
[Guest]: you're giving away a certain portion of your rights, but no more. Yeah, that's, that's

01:08:36.520 --> 01:08:40.960
[Guest]: Yeah, but that's why I just I think the negative positive is not fully revealed.

01:08:40.960 --> 01:08:47.800
[Amit Varma]: So civil political versus socioeconomic. Let's kind of move on to the third element of your

01:08:47.800 --> 01:08:53.380
[Amit Varma]: codification chapter, which is the debate between procedural and substantive due process.

01:08:53.380 --> 01:08:54.480
[Amit Varma]: What are these?

01:08:54.480 --> 01:09:00.600
[Guest]: So you know, it's simple, I hope, which is that procedural due process is basically a

01:09:00.600 --> 01:09:07.720
[Guest]: situation where your right to life or personal liberty can be taken away, so long as you

01:09:07.720 --> 01:09:14.040
[Guest]: follow the procedure in the law. It's as simple as that, right? So if the procedure says that,

01:09:14.040 --> 01:09:18.960
[Guest]: look, person has to be arrested, has to be given a lawyer has to be told, as long as

01:09:18.960 --> 01:09:24.320
[Guest]: you've done all that, it's fine. Now, obviously, if that is what you're guaranteeing, then

01:09:24.320 --> 01:09:30.440
[Guest]: that is a check on the executive, right? Because the executive has to follow the law. But Parliament

01:09:30.440 --> 01:09:37.120
[Guest]: has a lot of freedom in framing the law. A second is substantive due process, where you're

01:09:37.120 --> 01:09:42.760
[Guest]: saying, look, not only do you actually have to, not only does the executive has to follow

01:09:42.760 --> 01:09:49.900
[Guest]: the law created by Parliament, the law created by Parliament itself has to have certain amounts

01:09:49.900 --> 01:09:56.080
[Guest]: of fairness, rule of law type considerations, right? So that itself actually has to have

01:09:56.080 --> 01:10:03.560
[Guest]: certain inbuilt requirements. Now, again, in this situation, the debate about how to

01:10:03.560 --> 01:10:10.160
[Guest]: codify this provision, how to actually give it textual character, was not a debate over

01:10:10.160 --> 01:10:17.120
[Guest]: whether you want the state to have more or less power. Like in the case of rights, like

01:10:17.120 --> 01:10:21.880
[Guest]: in the case of directive principles, one of the themes I've tried to run throughout successfully

01:10:21.880 --> 01:10:29.120
[Guest]: unsuccessfully, is that these were all debates actually about how you should write something.

01:10:29.120 --> 01:10:38.400
[Guest]: These were not varying visions, right? Nobody who argued for restrictions on free speech

01:10:38.400 --> 01:10:44.520
[Guest]: in the Constitution had a less generous view of free speech. That's the interesting thing,

01:10:44.520 --> 01:10:47.920
[Guest]: right? So then you could ask, what were they thinking? Maybe they were wrong to think that.

01:10:47.920 --> 01:10:51.600
[Guest]: But at the end of the day, they all are thinking that that is itself what makes free speech

01:10:51.600 --> 01:10:56.160
[Guest]: possible. They are thinking that, look, actually, you put in no restrictions tomorrow, other

01:10:56.160 --> 01:11:01.840
[Guest]: bodies who we don't trust could impose 10 more restrictions. Now, the puzzle here is

01:11:01.840 --> 01:11:09.120
[Guest]: that if you recognize substantive due process, which means that you give the legislature

01:11:09.120 --> 01:11:16.120
[Guest]: very little power or less power, then because you're also going to judge the laws that they

01:11:16.120 --> 01:11:22.880
[Guest]: create, then you could prevent very radical economic legislation, like property redistribution,

01:11:22.880 --> 01:11:27.760
[Guest]: because there could be debates about on what test will you judge that law. On the other

01:11:27.760 --> 01:11:34.200
[Guest]: hand, if you actually only allow procedural due process, you will give the legislature

01:11:34.200 --> 01:11:40.480
[Guest]: very large powers. And the danger with that is that you will allow preventive detention.

01:11:40.480 --> 01:11:45.800
[Guest]: Now, the interesting thing about this debate, Amit, is neither side wants extreme preventive

01:11:45.800 --> 01:11:50.720
[Guest]: detention, neither side wants to limit economic redistribution. But the question is, which

01:11:50.720 --> 01:11:57.160
[Guest]: textual provision will give you what? So it again captures the neutrality of the harmony

01:11:57.160 --> 01:12:03.920
[Guest]: between both sides. And ultimately, what you get is you resolve the issue by doing procedural

01:12:03.920 --> 01:12:10.040
[Guest]: due process, but by actually having a separate set of provisions in the Constitution, Article

01:12:10.040 --> 01:12:16.760
[Guest]: 22, that provide certain safeguards in cases of preventive detention. Like you need to

01:12:16.760 --> 01:12:20.800
[Guest]: have a lawyer, you need to be told all things like that, double jeopardy, those kinds of

01:12:20.800 --> 01:12:26.040
[Amit Varma]: things. So in a sense, these guys are not just debating what the Constitution should

01:12:26.040 --> 01:12:31.640
[Amit Varma]: do. It's not so much a debate over ends per se, but they're also debating how the Constitution

01:12:31.640 --> 01:12:35.760
[Amit Varma]: should achieve that, how it should be written. So it's at this meta level, where they're

01:12:35.760 --> 01:12:41.320
[Guest]: having to think about this completely. I mean, these are a group of people who are basically

01:12:41.320 --> 01:12:51.000
[Guest]: saying, look, after us, in a year, the whole country will be governed through popular authorization.

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:57.200
[Guest]: What will that do to people? How will they behave? And what document do they need to

01:12:57.200 --> 01:13:02.360
[Guest]: actually understand how to behave? I can't limit them. They could change the Constitution

01:13:02.360 --> 01:13:07.520
[Guest]: or they could burn it. But assume that they want to take it seriously. What guidance can

01:13:07.520 --> 01:13:12.680
[Guest]: I provide to them? If they say, yeah, people have told us, protect free speech. I don't

01:13:12.680 --> 01:13:16.400
[Guest]: even know what free speech is. If people will say protect due process, I don't even know

01:13:16.400 --> 01:13:21.320
[Guest]: what these things mean. So the Constitution in that sense, this is a phrase I use later

01:13:21.320 --> 01:13:27.800
[Guest]: in the book, is in most countries in the West, it's a rule book. In India, it's also a textbook.

01:13:27.800 --> 01:13:33.400
[Guest]: The whole idea is that you're actually explaining these concepts, because they are not understood

01:13:33.400 --> 01:13:34.400
[Guest]: by anyone.

01:13:34.400 --> 01:13:38.640
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's interesting that it's often being joked, like what you point out is that because

01:13:38.640 --> 01:13:45.120
[Amit Varma]: we are a democracy, the facility to change the Constitution is, you know, freely available

01:13:45.120 --> 01:13:50.360
[Amit Varma]: to elected politicians. And this has been freely used. Like, at one point, it was joked

01:13:50.360 --> 01:13:54.760
[Amit Varma]: that the Constitution is not a book, but a periodical. And Nehru changed it very often,

01:13:54.760 --> 01:13:59.560
[Amit Varma]: Indira, of course, famously. And, you know, you spoke of burning, Ambedkar said, I think,

01:13:59.560 --> 01:14:04.560
[Amit Varma]: in 53 or 54, that if I had my way, I would just have burned the Constitution. As an aside,

01:14:04.560 --> 01:14:06.960
[Amit Varma]: before we go to a commercial break, what made him so frustrated?

01:14:06.960 --> 01:14:13.160
[Guest]: I mean, I think those are very specific debates about sort of Hindu reform, about the nature

01:14:13.160 --> 01:14:17.200
[Guest]: in which change is occurring in an independent India. So that, I mean, one of the things

01:14:17.200 --> 01:14:22.840
[Guest]: Amit, I consciously try to do is make sure that I don't spend too much time post 1950.

01:14:22.840 --> 01:14:28.200
[Guest]: A, because then those dynamics become very different. And B, also, then I suffer the

01:14:28.200 --> 01:14:33.040
[Guest]: problem of having to update my book, which I don't want to do, because I'm kind of lazy.

01:14:33.040 --> 01:14:35.160
[Amit Varma]: So this is great. So I end at 1950.

01:14:35.160 --> 01:14:39.520
[Amit Varma]: Excellent. And we'll take a quick commercial break. And after we come back, the meat of

01:14:39.520 --> 01:14:44.040
[Amit Varma]: the book is still left. So we shall talk about that.

