01:15:54.960 --> 01:15:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with Madhav Khosla on his amazing

01:15:58.000 --> 01:16:06.040
[Amit Varma]: book India's founding moment, which is essentially divided into three themes where he looks at

01:16:06.040 --> 01:16:12.040
[Amit Varma]: these three sort of locations of debate at the time the constitution was being formed.

01:16:12.040 --> 01:16:17.480
[Amit Varma]: One, as we have discussed, is the codification, both in the sense of the extreme amount of

01:16:17.480 --> 01:16:23.240
[Amit Varma]: codification that the book had, and also, you know, illustrating that through how they

01:16:23.240 --> 01:16:28.560
[Amit Varma]: looked at directive principles, how they looked at the rights, which they did guarantee, but

01:16:28.560 --> 01:16:34.440
[Amit Varma]: attach caveats to, and in the whole question of procedural versus substantive due process.

01:16:34.440 --> 01:16:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Now we come to sort of your second chapter of your book, which is about how we chose

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:45.280
[Amit Varma]: such a centralized model. Now, I'd done an episode with the historian Gyan Prakash on

01:16:45.280 --> 01:16:49.960
[Amit Varma]: his book on the emergency. And he pointed out during that episode and indeed in his

01:16:49.960 --> 01:16:55.720
[Amit Varma]: book, that one of the reasons that so much power was centralized, which is why everything

01:16:55.720 --> 01:16:59.940
[Amit Varma]: Indira Gandhi did was absolutely alleged by the constitution. One of the reasons so much

01:16:59.940 --> 01:17:05.120
[Amit Varma]: power was centralized was that the framers of our constitution at the time they were

01:17:05.120 --> 01:17:09.680
[Amit Varma]: framing the constitution, there was violence breaking out all over the country, there was

01:17:09.680 --> 01:17:14.600
[Amit Varma]: no guarantee that the center would hold. So hey, the centralized power for that reason,

01:17:14.600 --> 01:17:22.040
[Amit Varma]: but as you point out in your book, debates around that had been going on for decades,

01:17:22.040 --> 01:17:27.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, and Gandhi was, of course, one of the prominent voices against centralization.

01:17:27.720 --> 01:17:32.320
[Amit Varma]: So were people like Radhakamal Mukherjee, who wrote the book, democracies of the East,

01:17:32.320 --> 01:17:36.080
[Amit Varma]: which which I found fascinating, and I hadn't heard of it before. So, and you've quoted

01:17:36.080 --> 01:17:41.120
[Amit Varma]: elaborately from that. So give me a sense of, you know, through the decades before independence

01:17:41.120 --> 01:17:46.520
[Amit Varma]: is even a remote possibility. How are people thinking of this relationship between state

01:17:46.520 --> 01:17:47.520
[Guest]: and society?

01:17:47.520 --> 01:17:54.280
[Guest]: So, Amit, you know, I began thinking about this chapter with the preconception that I

01:17:54.280 --> 01:18:00.560
[Guest]: think a lot of people have, one that you just gestured at, which was that look, partition

01:18:00.560 --> 01:18:07.280
[Guest]: happened, there's civil war, and a strong centralized state is what can prevent India

01:18:07.280 --> 01:18:11.920
[Guest]: from breaking up into smaller states. It can prevent further partition, it can prevent

01:18:11.920 --> 01:18:16.840
[Guest]: the balkanization of the new country. And so I thought that look, a centralized state

01:18:16.840 --> 01:18:25.560
[Guest]: is basically a contingent outcome of a serious security concern and of fear. And then the

01:18:25.560 --> 01:18:31.080
[Guest]: more you read the debates, you realize that's not actually true. So there's a you realize

01:18:31.080 --> 01:18:37.680
[Guest]: that there's a deep ideological and theoretical vision behind centralization. And we need

01:18:37.680 --> 01:18:44.160
[Guest]: to think a little bit about what that vision was, right. Now, the Constituent Assembly

01:18:44.160 --> 01:18:52.600
[Guest]: meets under the 1946 Cabinet Mission Plan, right? And the Cabinet Mission Plan is a failure.

01:18:52.600 --> 01:18:56.840
[Guest]: Under the Cabinet Mission Plan, there is not that much centralization, right? It's a federation

01:18:56.840 --> 01:19:03.560
[Guest]: of a complex kind. And once the Cabinet Mission Plan fails, when India becomes divided, because

01:19:03.560 --> 01:19:09.200
[Guest]: under the Cabinet Mission Plan, it was one united country. Basically, people in the Constituent

01:19:09.200 --> 01:19:13.000
[Guest]: Assembly are thrilled, because they're like, look, now we have freedom, we can make any

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:18.040
[Guest]: country we want, we are not governed by the provisions of the plan. And then you see a

01:19:18.040 --> 01:19:22.880
[Guest]: debate about centralization. And there are two broad traditions. And I think the best

01:19:22.880 --> 01:19:30.000
[Guest]: way to understand the centralization debate is to see it as a contrast between the state

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:37.040
[Guest]: and society. So on the one hand, you have people like Gandhi, like Radha Kamal Mukherjee,

01:19:37.040 --> 01:19:43.800
[Guest]: who want something called political pluralism. And let's pause for a moment, because it's

01:19:43.800 --> 01:19:53.360
[Guest]: quite a complicated idea. In our societies, the state is at the center of authority, the

01:19:53.360 --> 01:20:02.560
[Guest]: state is the exclusive authority. A society that has political pluralism is one where

01:20:02.560 --> 01:20:10.280
[Guest]: a range of bodies in society exercise authority, professional guilds, associations, organizations,

01:20:10.280 --> 01:20:15.640
[Guest]: and the state is one among them, there's nothing special about the state. And what was interesting

01:20:15.640 --> 01:20:22.160
[Guest]: in Mukherjee and Gandhi's vision, is that you would have these extremely decentralized

01:20:22.160 --> 01:20:28.520
[Guest]: village republics, where there would be authority split everywhere. And so its authority is

01:20:28.520 --> 01:20:34.480
[Guest]: more and more dispersed, think about it as a dispersal of power through and through.

01:20:34.480 --> 01:20:39.960
[Guest]: And that in a way would provide some kind of freedom. So it is a vision of democracy,

01:20:39.960 --> 01:20:46.640
[Guest]: make no mistake about it. It's a vision of democracy, that places a huge amount of emphasis

01:20:46.640 --> 01:20:54.200
[Guest]: on participation, and on local attention, and on local engagement, right. And it is

01:20:54.200 --> 01:21:05.880
[Guest]: a vision of democracy, where there is a critique of the modernized, civilized, Western conception

01:21:05.880 --> 01:21:12.000
[Guest]: of progress, because that is associated with a certain kind of violence. Now on the alternative

01:21:12.000 --> 01:21:18.320
[Guest]: side of the spectrum, you also have a vision of democracy. There the vision of democracy

01:21:18.320 --> 01:21:24.520
[Guest]: comes from the idea that look, everybody in India sees each other differently. They see

01:21:24.520 --> 01:21:31.680
[Guest]: each other through narrow, localized, and localism is the enemy of equality. Because

01:21:31.680 --> 01:21:38.160
[Guest]: ultimately, if I see you as belonging to X village, Y caste, C religion, speaking A language,

01:21:38.160 --> 01:21:43.520
[Guest]: B dialect, I'm not seeing you as a human being, I'm not seeing you as an individual. And the

01:21:43.520 --> 01:21:53.440
[Guest]: way to actually make me see you as an individual is to dismantle those prior forms of authority,

01:21:53.440 --> 01:21:59.480
[Guest]: and to actually place us all under one umbrella. And that one umbrella is the state. So the

01:21:59.480 --> 01:22:05.840
[Guest]: minute we all get under one umbrella, we actually come under the state. So that's the two very

01:22:05.840 --> 01:22:10.520
[Guest]: different visions of democracy. And they rest on two very different visions of the society

01:22:10.520 --> 01:22:16.400
[Guest]: and the state. On the one hand, society can be the site of change. And society can be

01:22:16.400 --> 01:22:23.560
[Guest]: the site of freedom. And the state is a violent force, right, that just coerces people. On

01:22:23.560 --> 01:22:30.080
[Guest]: the other hand, society is what needs to be destroyed, quite literally. And actually,

01:22:30.080 --> 01:22:35.440
[Guest]: the state is the force that can enable us to see each other differently. Now, the question

01:22:35.440 --> 01:22:42.480
[Guest]: that you can ask is, look, why is it that the Pluralists lost out? And the Pluralists

01:22:42.480 --> 01:22:48.800
[Guest]: lost out for the same reason that they lost out everywhere. And by everywhere, I mean

01:22:48.800 --> 01:22:55.840
[Guest]: that this was part of a big global movement, also in the UK, most famously, but also elsewhere.

01:22:55.840 --> 01:23:01.420
[Guest]: And the Pluralists lost out everywhere. And by lost out, what do I mean? I mean that look,

01:23:01.420 --> 01:23:08.720
[Guest]: one of the important, noteworthy, startling features of the mid 20th century is that for

01:23:08.720 --> 01:23:14.560
[Guest]: 50 years before that, you have a range of proposals, right, to move beyond the nation

01:23:14.560 --> 01:23:19.760
[Guest]: state, right, all kinds of federations, you have a range of proposals for certain kinds

01:23:19.760 --> 01:23:31.080
[Guest]: of Pluralism. But ultimately, what happens is that the 20th century marks the centrality

01:23:31.080 --> 01:23:36.520
[Guest]: of the nation state and its victory over other institutional forms. And the Pluralists lose

01:23:36.520 --> 01:23:44.040
[Guest]: out because they never have an argument for actually how you can, through the logic of

01:23:44.040 --> 01:23:51.560
[Guest]: society without a state, preserve peace and enable a certain kind of freedom. So when

01:23:51.560 --> 01:23:59.280
[Guest]: somebody will say that, look, how can you actually ensure that Hindus and Muslims will

01:23:59.280 --> 01:24:07.160
[Guest]: not fight? The Pluralist answer will be, look, be good to your neighbours. They've not fought

01:24:07.160 --> 01:24:11.420
[Guest]: before. If they fought before, then they find a way to deal with it. It has happened for

01:24:11.420 --> 01:24:18.400
[Guest]: so many years, it will happen for more years. By happen, I mean the resolution, right? That

01:24:18.400 --> 01:24:24.480
[Guest]: is not good enough as an answer to people who have such a deep fear of that situation

01:24:24.480 --> 01:24:30.720
[Guest]: because they say, look, you actually need a force, a genuine force to attack and to

01:24:30.720 --> 01:24:36.280
[Guest]: respond to society. You cannot just say society will find a way because it has found a way

01:24:36.280 --> 01:24:41.920
[Guest]: all the time before. So the difference is that the reason for the failure is that they

01:24:41.920 --> 01:24:48.640
[Guest]: cannot offer a conceptual answer for the reasons for which the state had been imagined in the

01:24:48.640 --> 01:24:55.400
[Guest]: first place. Their answer is a kind of sociology, or it's a kind of history, right? Where they

01:24:55.400 --> 01:24:59.080
[Guest]: say, look, it's happened before, people have been fighting for long, they find a way to

01:24:59.080 --> 01:25:03.480
[Guest]: deal with it. Whereas if I'm terrified that two people are going to kill each other, I

01:25:03.480 --> 01:25:06.920
[Guest]: want an answer to why they wouldn't do it. And the answer why they wouldn't do it is

01:25:06.920 --> 01:25:10.520
[Guest]: because one of them would be jailed. And so that answer is the state.

01:25:10.520 --> 01:25:15.320
[Amit Varma]: In fact, this reminds me of what my great liberal hero, Frederick Hayek, once wrote

01:25:15.320 --> 01:25:20.920
[Amit Varma]: in an essay called why I am not a conservative, where he pointed out that, you know, conservatives

01:25:20.920 --> 01:25:26.040
[Amit Varma]: will always have things to say about the means of change, but they will not have, they will

01:25:26.040 --> 01:25:31.400
[Amit Varma]: not be able to explain how change will happen in the first place. They will have no specific

01:25:31.400 --> 01:25:37.040
[Amit Varma]: ends of their own, which is something I explored in an episode also with Jyothi Thrao on his

01:25:37.040 --> 01:25:41.680
[Amit Varma]: recent book, The Indian Conservative, which reminded me of this argument against the pluralist

01:25:41.680 --> 01:25:47.800
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, how will you make change happen? My sort of question here is, I totally get

01:25:47.800 --> 01:25:54.840
[Amit Varma]: the logic against localism, that when you have divisive, dangerous, unpredictable localism,

01:25:54.840 --> 01:26:00.720
[Amit Varma]: the urge for centralization and to bring it under one set of values is very coherent to

01:26:00.720 --> 01:26:05.840
[Amit Varma]: me. But what I would argue for and what, you know, in India has sometimes been paid lip

01:26:05.840 --> 01:26:11.000
[Amit Varma]: service to is that you centralize your values through the rules of the constitution or the

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:15.960
[Amit Varma]: textbook, the constitution, you centralize your values, but you decentralize governance,

01:26:15.960 --> 01:26:21.480
[Amit Varma]: where governance becomes as local as possible all the way down to cities and towns in Panchayati

01:26:21.480 --> 01:26:27.240
[Amit Varma]: Raj. And what that does is that it creates a link between power and accountability, which

01:26:27.240 --> 01:26:32.760
[Amit Varma]: doesn't exist today because our system is so dysfunctional. It increases the value of

01:26:32.760 --> 01:26:37.560
[Amit Varma]: a vote because you will actually feel assured that your vote is far likelier to make a difference

01:26:37.560 --> 01:26:43.480
[Amit Varma]: at that level. And therefore, citizens become more concerned and educate themselves better,

01:26:43.480 --> 01:26:49.840
[Amit Varma]: their incentives get better. And that's the sort of, so when I talk about the desirability

01:26:49.840 --> 01:26:55.440
[Amit Varma]: of a decentralized state, that's what I mean. And you have your values centralized in the

01:26:55.440 --> 01:27:00.040
[Amit Varma]: constitution and the laws that govern you, but you have your governance decentralized,

01:27:00.040 --> 01:27:01.520
[Guest]: so democracy can be more efficient.

01:27:01.520 --> 01:27:08.080
[Guest]: No, I certainly think that India has, I mean, one of the many ills in India's constitution

01:27:08.080 --> 01:27:13.080
[Guest]: model today is the kind of centralization, right? I think the important thing to think

01:27:13.080 --> 01:27:20.800
[Guest]: about is at that moment, the fear of decentralization, even of the kinds that you describe, right,

01:27:20.800 --> 01:27:25.880
[Guest]: or of like, you could, I mean, there are ways to think that centralize on some things, decentralize

01:27:25.880 --> 01:27:31.960
[Guest]: on others, so on and so forth. And this is just what's interesting to learn, right, is

01:27:31.960 --> 01:27:38.280
[Guest]: that the fear of society is so deep that there's a sense that, look, the more you go down,

01:27:38.280 --> 01:27:44.840
[Guest]: the more society will permeate the state, right? And actually, therefore, radicalism

01:27:44.840 --> 01:27:51.160
[Guest]: requires some distance, which is why people who are critical of this are saying, look,

01:27:51.160 --> 01:27:57.240
[Guest]: we're doing imperialism 2.0, because the whole point that radicalism requires distance was

01:27:57.240 --> 01:28:03.120
[Guest]: the colonial argument. So, it's a very interesting contest between both sides. And I think it's

01:28:03.120 --> 01:28:09.720
[Guest]: also worth noting, because you referenced the word conservative a moment ago, depending

01:28:09.720 --> 01:28:17.200
[Guest]: on where you stand, people like Gandhi and Mukherjee are either conservative or radical,

01:28:17.200 --> 01:28:20.920
[Guest]: because at one level, they are radical, because they are saying, look, Indian society itself

01:28:20.920 --> 01:28:26.160
[Guest]: can do it. You don't even need the state. That's also radical. Gandhi had a profoundly

01:28:26.160 --> 01:28:30.920
[Guest]: radical view of human agency. Not only did he believe that people were capable of what

01:28:30.920 --> 01:28:37.720
[Guest]: we might think are extraordinary things, he thought every person is capable of that. So,

01:28:37.720 --> 01:28:44.280
[Guest]: I think what's important in the contest between people like Ambedkar, Nehru versus a Gandhi-Mukherjee

01:28:44.280 --> 01:28:51.400
[Guest]: type thing is both sides claim radicalism, and both sides claim democracy. I think what

01:28:51.400 --> 01:28:57.520
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi and Mukherjee do, and tell me if you agree, is that their ends are radical, but

01:28:57.520 --> 01:29:02.480
[Guest]: their means are conservative. No, they would say that their ends are deep, their means

01:29:02.480 --> 01:29:06.400
[Guest]: are deeply radical, because they say that it can happen through society itself. That's

01:29:06.400 --> 01:29:09.920
[Amit Varma]: a conservative statement that you don't need the coercive power of the state that society

01:29:09.920 --> 01:29:14.480
[Amit Varma]: will reform itself where required. That's exactly the classic conservative position,

01:29:14.480 --> 01:29:18.640
[Guest]: isn't it? That's what Burke would say. No, because they would say that, look, it's so

01:29:18.640 --> 01:29:28.440
[Guest]: much more radical that the change lies within, that I can actually change within. That's

01:29:28.440 --> 01:29:35.840
[Guest]: radical. It's conservative to think that some external force will do it. Their whole metaphor

01:29:35.840 --> 01:29:41.240
[Guest]: of the state is an external force. They see the state simply like colonialism, just as

01:29:41.240 --> 01:29:46.960
[Guest]: an external force. If somebody were to tell you, Amit, there are ABC things you can change,

01:29:46.960 --> 01:29:51.160
[Guest]: and either change them by talking to these people, or change them within just on your

01:29:51.160 --> 01:29:56.920
[Guest]: own. You would say that changing them on my own is like too radical. Like, it's like that

01:29:56.920 --> 01:30:02.600
[Guest]: requires too much almost. Like there's a different level of evolution needed for that kind of

01:30:02.600 --> 01:30:07.360
[Amit Varma]: and that's their answer. I think I'd interpret these terms slightly differently, but moving

01:30:07.360 --> 01:30:13.600
[Guest]: on. Yeah, I mean, I would just say that both sides claim radicalism, and both sides claim

01:30:13.600 --> 01:30:17.240
[Guest]: democracy. I think that's what I would say. I'm not saying you have to agree or disagree,

01:30:17.240 --> 01:30:21.800
[Guest]: right? The very fact that there are multiple definitions of these terms is why they can

01:30:21.800 --> 01:30:26.840
[Amit Varma]: both claim it. Fair enough. You also cite, you know, it's very interesting that, you

01:30:26.840 --> 01:30:31.960
[Amit Varma]: know, Lasky was a big influence on Nehru and a hero of Nehru, and yet Lasky has a different

01:30:31.960 --> 01:30:36.280
[Amit Varma]: view on this subject than Nehru does. And from your book, you write, I'll quote from

01:30:36.280 --> 01:30:42.320
[Amit Varma]: that, quote for Lasky, the emphasis on state coercion had been a philosophical and sociological

01:30:42.320 --> 01:30:47.680
[Amit Varma]: error. It had presented a model of power that failed to pay due attention to the reality

01:30:47.680 --> 01:30:53.280
[Amit Varma]: of consent. And later on, you quote P.T. Chacko saying during the debates, quote, in the place

01:30:53.280 --> 01:30:58.560
[Amit Varma]: of foreign imperialism, we are now having an Indian imperialism, stop quote. And many

01:30:58.560 --> 01:31:03.800
[Amit Varma]: would say looking at, for example, what is happening in Kashmir now, you know, many would

01:31:03.800 --> 01:31:08.920
[Amit Varma]: turn to Lasky's point about the consent of the government and the way the central government

01:31:08.920 --> 01:31:13.560
[Amit Varma]: could just declare Kashmir a non-state and split it up into union territories. Doesn't

01:31:13.560 --> 01:31:17.560
[Amit Varma]: that show that there was something profound in the warnings of those who warned against

01:31:17.560 --> 01:31:19.800
[Guest]: such a powerful centralized state?

01:31:19.800 --> 01:31:24.520
[Guest]: So two things. One, just as a specific point of intellectual history, you're right that

01:31:24.520 --> 01:31:30.920
[Guest]: as site Lasky is a pluralist, Lasky changes his view later. Right. And so he then becomes

01:31:30.920 --> 01:31:37.600
[Guest]: a state guy. And that's the best sort of book that explains the Lasky and switch. And it's

01:31:37.600 --> 01:31:43.520
[Guest]: the best among the best books on pluralism is a book by David Runciman, which I reference.

01:31:43.520 --> 01:31:47.800
[Guest]: The second is that I think the short answer that a lot of people would give you is yes,

01:31:47.800 --> 01:31:56.040
[Guest]: you're right. I mean, I think the state seems to be exercising extraordinary coercive power

01:31:56.040 --> 01:32:04.080
[Guest]: significantly more than what any of us associated with modern constitutional democracies. Now,

01:32:04.080 --> 01:32:10.400
[Guest]: how that has happened and how that will change is a question probably above one's pay grade.

01:32:10.400 --> 01:32:15.240
[Guest]: But I think that it's certainly true that more and more, the state is behaving less

01:32:15.240 --> 01:32:18.880
[Guest]: and less like the state in a free society.

01:32:18.880 --> 01:32:25.160
[Amit Varma]: And I just want to clarify for my listeners that my sort of what you have described beautifully

01:32:25.160 --> 01:32:30.880
[Amit Varma]: here is the arguments that led to the centralization of the state. Nowhere have you actually defended

01:32:30.880 --> 01:32:35.360
[Amit Varma]: it or argued for it. In fact, you've been pretty scrupulous in giving both sides of

01:32:35.360 --> 01:32:42.000
[Amit Varma]: the debate and talking about, you know, how we sort of got here. Let's talk about the

01:32:42.000 --> 01:32:47.200
[Amit Varma]: third locus of your book, which is very complicated and which also is like a two part question.

01:32:47.200 --> 01:32:53.760
[Amit Varma]: And that's a question of identity. India, at its founding, does have the huge Hindu

01:32:53.760 --> 01:32:59.080
[Amit Varma]: Muslim problem to deal with. And you've quoted from, you know, Jinnah's presidential address

01:32:59.080 --> 01:33:04.040
[Amit Varma]: at the All India Muslim League conference in 1940, where he explains in great detail

01:33:04.040 --> 01:33:10.240
[Amit Varma]: why Hindus and Muslims are two separate nations and they cannot possibly live together. You've

01:33:10.240 --> 01:33:15.280
[Amit Varma]: quoted Nehru expressing his contempt for group based thinking. And at the same time, you've

01:33:15.280 --> 01:33:21.360
[Amit Varma]: also cited from Ambedkar's book, Pakistan or the partition of India, where he points

01:33:21.360 --> 01:33:28.480
[Amit Varma]: out that the argument behind Pakistan has some merit to it and, you know, should not

01:33:28.480 --> 01:33:33.680
[Amit Varma]: be caricatured. And also at one point he talks about, which I found very interesting in the

01:33:33.680 --> 01:33:37.960
[Amit Varma]: present context, where he talks about why Hindu nationalists and the Indian National

01:33:37.960 --> 01:33:42.520
[Amit Varma]: Congress have both failed in dealing with the problem. Because as he says it, the Hindu

01:33:42.520 --> 01:33:46.760
[Amit Varma]: nationalists want to just do away with Muslims and the Indian National Congress wants to

01:33:46.760 --> 01:33:50.880
[Amit Varma]: appease them and pander to them. And that doesn't help either. Can you elaborate a bit

01:33:50.880 --> 01:33:56.120
[Amit Varma]: on the sort of pre-independence debates that were happening around this question?

01:33:56.120 --> 01:34:03.360
[Guest]: Completely. So the interesting thing about the years prior to the birth of modern India

01:34:03.360 --> 01:34:10.440
[Guest]: is that there is a deep crisis of liberal representation, by which I mean that you are

01:34:10.440 --> 01:34:16.880
[Guest]: not seeing people as individuals. You are seeing them as members of groups and you are

01:34:16.880 --> 01:34:24.680
[Guest]: seeing citizenship as mediated through group identity. So if you see Muslim nationalists,

01:34:24.680 --> 01:34:30.840
[Guest]: Jinnah is the most famous example. But I also think that somebody like Moulana Azad is very

01:34:30.840 --> 01:34:36.920
[Guest]: interesting. And I think the problem that's happened is this, Amit, that all of our historical

01:34:36.920 --> 01:34:42.080
[Guest]: attention is on partition, which is a question of territoriality. Did you want one country

01:34:42.080 --> 01:34:47.120
[Guest]: or two? If you change the focus and say, I'm not interested in the question of do you want

01:34:47.120 --> 01:34:52.440
[Guest]: one country or two, but I'm interested in the question actually of do you see people

01:34:52.440 --> 01:34:58.480
[Guest]: as equal or as different? The question of whether you keep them as equal or different

01:34:58.480 --> 01:35:02.040
[Guest]: and you could keep them as different in one country or in two, but do you see them as

01:35:02.040 --> 01:35:07.600
[Guest]: equal or different, right? If you ask that question, you're no longer interested in territoriality,

01:35:07.600 --> 01:35:14.040
[Guest]: but you're interested in representation. And then your interesting date is not 1947. It's

01:35:14.040 --> 01:35:22.720
[Guest]: 1909. It's the Mali Minto reforms onwards. From that period to 1947, you barely find

01:35:22.720 --> 01:35:25.460
[Guest]: anyone who's seeing people as the same.

01:35:25.460 --> 01:35:29.280
[Amit Varma]: And just to clarify what the Mali Minto reforms did was it created separate electorates for

01:35:29.280 --> 01:35:30.480
[Amit Varma]: Hindus and Muslims.

01:35:30.480 --> 01:35:36.040
[Guest]: So basically, since that period, somebody like Jinnah is seeing them as different and

01:35:36.040 --> 01:35:42.360
[Guest]: asking for two countries. Somebody like Moulana Azad is seeing them as actually asking for

01:35:42.360 --> 01:35:46.280
[Guest]: one country, but I think it's not clear that he's seeing them as the same. He never really

01:35:46.280 --> 01:35:52.760
[Guest]: gives up on Sharia. And I discussed the intellectual origins of how far back this goes. In the

01:35:52.760 --> 01:35:57.200
[Guest]: case of, I mean, it goes all the way back to Sayyar Ahmed Khan famously. So in the case

01:35:57.200 --> 01:36:03.480
[Guest]: of Hindu nationalism, they see everybody as the same, but everybody's Hindu. So they effectively,

01:36:03.480 --> 01:36:09.720
[Guest]: it means an elimination of the minority completely. And the group, which is the Indian National

01:36:09.720 --> 01:36:16.240
[Guest]: Congress, which unambiguously wants one country and unambiguously hates communalism in some

01:36:16.240 --> 01:36:22.320
[Guest]: sense doesn't give us a very clear model either, because it's not that interested in this question.

01:36:22.320 --> 01:36:28.280
[Guest]: But for most of his life, somebody like Nehru at that time, not for most of his life, but

01:36:28.280 --> 01:36:33.680
[Guest]: for most of those years, is interested in actually economic issues. And he sees differences

01:36:33.680 --> 01:36:38.280
[Guest]: as exemplifying economic conflicts and as being a reflection of economic conflicts.

01:36:38.280 --> 01:36:42.640
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in your book, you write about how the Bengal conflict, he saw it not as a conflict

01:36:42.640 --> 01:36:45.640
[Amit Varma]: between Hindus and Muslims, but landlords and tenants.

01:36:45.640 --> 01:36:51.040
[Guest]: Completely. And you see those examples can be easily multiplied. Similarly, sorry, in

01:36:51.040 --> 01:36:57.480
[Guest]: a different way, Gandhi is also somebody who doesn't take the question seriously at the

01:36:57.480 --> 01:37:02.800
[Guest]: level of theory because he's interested in practice. Gandhi's answer is, look, you treat

01:37:02.800 --> 01:37:07.820
[Guest]: your neighbor well, right? He doesn't have a model of representation because he's aiming

01:37:07.820 --> 01:37:13.440
[Guest]: for a very different political vision. Now, that basically means that it's only after

01:37:13.440 --> 01:37:20.160
[Guest]: partition that you get a situation where you have to come up with a theory of representation.

01:37:20.160 --> 01:37:26.540
[Guest]: And you see two things happening in that moment in Indian history. The first is that you see

01:37:26.540 --> 01:37:33.440
[Guest]: a move towards individual representation. So, the assembly rejects separate electorates,

01:37:33.440 --> 01:37:40.320
[Guest]: it rejects weightage on religious grounds, it rejects reservations on religious grounds.

01:37:40.320 --> 01:37:48.240
[Guest]: Because they say that, look, any model that is structured around identity cannot work.

01:37:48.240 --> 01:37:54.760
[Guest]: It cannot create a sustainable political environment. And how do we know that? Because we've tried

01:37:54.760 --> 01:38:02.280
[Guest]: it. We have actually been trying since the last 40 years, a model. And if you are involved

01:38:02.280 --> 01:38:09.080
[Guest]: in this kind of trap, then what Pratap Bhanu Mehta once called Savarkar's trap, you can

01:38:09.080 --> 01:38:13.840
[Guest]: never get a solution out of it. If this is your question, all answers are wrong. Because

01:38:13.840 --> 01:38:21.000
[Guest]: if you're a majority, then you can never, if you take the majority view, the minority

01:38:21.000 --> 01:38:25.340
[Guest]: will be unhappy. If you take the minority view, the majority will be unhappy. And so

01:38:25.340 --> 01:38:32.320
[Guest]: you actually cannot ask the question in that way. The second thing they say is that, look,

01:38:32.320 --> 01:38:36.800
[Guest]: even to ask the question in that way is not only politically unsustainable in the way

01:38:36.800 --> 01:38:44.920
[Guest]: that we've seen, but it also actually is not a reflection of a democracy. Because the minute

01:38:44.920 --> 01:38:50.960
[Guest]: I am looking at people through certain identities, I'm doing that because I'm thinking that,

01:38:50.960 --> 01:38:56.280
[Guest]: look, a Muslim has a certain interest, a Hindu has a certain interest. But I only needed

01:38:56.280 --> 01:39:01.120
[Guest]: to do that. I only needed to guess people's interests in a British model where people

01:39:01.120 --> 01:39:06.000
[Guest]: were not expressing their interest. Now that people can go to the ballot box and vote,

01:39:06.000 --> 01:39:11.680
[Guest]: I don't need to identify them in any way. In fact, the only category that matters is

01:39:11.680 --> 01:39:17.320
[Guest]: political majority and political minority. And that is a category that is created and

01:39:17.320 --> 01:39:22.720
[Guest]: recreated through politics, which goes back to our initial theme. The whole point of a

01:39:22.720 --> 01:39:28.480
[Guest]: democracy is that I can make any world. To make any world, I need a majority and I can

01:39:28.480 --> 01:39:33.420
[Guest]: make any majority. Even if I'm one person who believes something, a democracy lets me

01:39:33.420 --> 01:39:38.960
[Guest]: convince everybody else and then we become a majority and we vote. So the only category

01:39:38.960 --> 01:39:44.680
[Guest]: that matters for the purposes of a democratic politics is a political majority and a political

01:39:44.680 --> 01:39:51.960
[Guest]: minority. And in order for it to be democratic, that must almost by definition be fluid. That

01:39:51.960 --> 01:39:57.360
[Guest]: can always be created and recreated. And so I can then always see people differently.

01:39:57.360 --> 01:40:02.760
[Guest]: Now the question that you might ask is, look, if people are so entrenched in seeing people

01:40:02.760 --> 01:40:07.480
[Guest]: as Hindus and Muslims, wouldn't they vote like that? And then the political majority

01:40:07.480 --> 01:40:15.960
[Guest]: and minority would mirror that. And here, the assembly comes up with getting a very

01:40:15.960 --> 01:40:22.640
[Guest]: interesting lesson from partition. Ultimately, what partition told you is that you created

01:40:22.640 --> 01:40:28.520
[Guest]: a huge communal problem where none existed. That means you put people in a specific institutional

01:40:28.520 --> 01:40:34.840
[Guest]: structure of separate electorates, of weightage, of reservations, all of this stuff, and you

01:40:34.840 --> 01:40:38.800
[Guest]: got them to think like that. You put them in a different structure, they won't think

01:40:38.800 --> 01:40:43.040
[Amit Varma]: like that. Right. And this is like the point that Sardar Patel, for example, made where

01:40:43.040 --> 01:40:47.960
[Amit Varma]: he said that separate electorates had sharpened communal differences because people would

01:40:47.960 --> 01:40:53.600
[Amit Varma]: see themselves as Hindus or Muslims and their participation would be along those lines.

01:40:53.600 --> 01:40:57.320
[Guest]: Exactly. And this goes back just to the initial theme that we talked about, which is the heart

01:40:57.320 --> 01:41:02.200
[Guest]: of the book, that you put people in any institutional structure, you'll get that. And so their point

01:41:02.200 --> 01:41:07.440
[Guest]: is you put people in an institutional structure where when you say majority-minority, they

01:41:07.440 --> 01:41:11.240
[Guest]: don't think Hindu-Muslim. They think political majority, political minority, and they're

01:41:11.240 --> 01:41:15.280
[Amit Varma]: always thinking, how can I change those? So then what the constitution does by removing

01:41:15.280 --> 01:41:20.640
[Amit Varma]: separate electorates is that it liberates you politically from having to think of yourself

01:41:20.640 --> 01:41:25.680
[Amit Varma]: as a Hindu. You might still feel that we're at the level of a community or society, but

01:41:25.680 --> 01:41:29.640
[Guest]: politically you can vote as an individual. Yeah, you can think any way you want. Nobody

01:41:29.640 --> 01:41:34.720
[Guest]: can stop you from doing that. But the point is that the relevant political category is

01:41:34.720 --> 01:41:41.920
[Amit Varma]: one actually of a political majority and minority. And so the separation of, you know, so you

01:41:41.920 --> 01:41:45.400
[Amit Varma]: did not have separate electorates. You just have one electorate and this is the reasoning

01:41:45.400 --> 01:41:51.280
[Guest]: behind it. Now, you also don't have reservations on religion and you don't have weightage.

01:41:51.280 --> 01:41:55.680
[Guest]: For all those years, it's not only separate electorates, there are a range of proposals

01:41:55.680 --> 01:41:59.560
[Guest]: that are being worked out in different ways, and all of them are rejected. And you would

01:41:59.560 --> 01:42:06.600
[Amit Varma]: assume that the arguments for rejecting them, for example, that they will increase the differences

01:42:06.600 --> 01:42:11.360
[Amit Varma]: between people, they will force people to think in those particular boxes, and so on

01:42:11.360 --> 01:42:17.160
[Amit Varma]: and so forth, are arguments that could also be used against caste. Now explain to me why,

01:42:17.160 --> 01:42:20.760
[Guest]: you know, that was looked at differently. Before that, Amit, if I could just pause you

01:42:20.760 --> 01:42:27.440
[Guest]: for a second, it's not only that it will make people think more like that. It's that that's

01:42:27.440 --> 01:42:32.320
[Guest]: not the relevant question for politics. I could make people think all the time like

01:42:32.320 --> 01:42:37.480
[Guest]: that or not at all like that. What's relevant in politics is not ethnic majority, it's political

01:42:37.480 --> 01:42:43.160
[Guest]: majority. And the minute I make it ethnic majority, I'm not letting myself create any

01:42:43.160 --> 01:42:49.240
[Guest]: political majority I want. So it's anti-democratic. Because you're basically saying that I can't

01:42:49.240 --> 01:42:55.400
[Guest]: create the identity I want in politics, the relevant identity being political majority,

01:42:55.400 --> 01:43:00.480
[Guest]: that identity is already given to me from outside. So that's outside the domain of politics,

01:43:00.480 --> 01:43:05.200
[Guest]: then I cannot actually be self ruling. Because to me, to be self ruling, I should be able

01:43:05.200 --> 01:43:10.320
[Amit Varma]: to collectively create that identity in politics. Then identity would be destiny. But here it's

01:43:10.320 --> 01:43:14.440
[Guest]: not you can make your own destiny. Exactly, exactly. Which is what it means to belong

01:43:14.440 --> 01:43:19.240
[Guest]: to the modern world. So as opposed to the ancient or medieval world. Yeah. So let's

01:43:19.240 --> 01:43:24.280
[Amit Varma]: do the modern world itself is changing. Yeah, but I mean, modern in a normative sense, not

01:43:24.280 --> 01:43:29.800
[Amit Varma]: in a descriptive sense. Yeah, absolutely. Let's talk about caste. You know, what are

01:43:29.800 --> 01:43:34.200
[Amit Varma]: the debates around that? And here is treated very differently from religion. And you've

01:43:34.200 --> 01:43:39.920
[Amit Varma]: sort of described the whole series of intellectual arguments around caste as well. And at some

01:43:39.920 --> 01:43:44.440
[Amit Varma]: level, of course, it mirrors the discussion we had earlier, where Gandhi is saying that,

01:43:44.440 --> 01:43:48.400
[Amit Varma]: let it change at the level of society. And Ambedkar is saying, Are you crazy? That's

01:43:48.400 --> 01:43:53.280
[Amit Varma]: never going to happen. We need the state to sort of step in. And at the same time, the

01:43:53.280 --> 01:43:57.920
[Amit Varma]: same sort of arguments which could be made against religious reservations can be made

01:43:57.920 --> 01:44:01.120
[Amit Varma]: against caste reservations, but they're not for a very good reason, which you elucidate.

01:44:01.120 --> 01:44:05.600
[Guest]: So tell me a bit about that. So I mean, this is a great question, right? Because the caste

01:44:05.600 --> 01:44:09.320
[Guest]: everything I've told you so far about religion, somebody could say, look, Madhav, this is

01:44:09.320 --> 01:44:14.200
[Guest]: well and good, but then why give reservations on caste, right? And I think nobody's quite

01:44:14.200 --> 01:44:19.160
[Guest]: answered this question. One answer has been look, it's an exception. That doesn't really

01:44:19.160 --> 01:44:25.280
[Guest]: explain it. Second is, oh, it's just contradictory, right? So I'm just sort of describing the

01:44:25.280 --> 01:44:31.520
[Guest]: conflict. I think that they actually fit together. And they fit together in the following way

01:44:31.520 --> 01:44:38.680
[Guest]: that firstly, there is an appreciation of the fact that caste tenders a different problem

01:44:38.680 --> 01:44:45.840
[Guest]: to religion. Namely, in religion, the challenge is how can I preserve religious freedom and

01:44:45.840 --> 01:44:52.840
[Guest]: allow people to vote on non-religious grounds and not mediate their citizenship through

01:44:52.840 --> 01:44:58.440
[Guest]: religion. In the case of caste, the goal is not accommodation, it's annihilation. I actually

01:44:58.440 --> 01:45:04.900
[Guest]: want to end caste. That's the first thing to be said. The second is that I actually

01:45:04.900 --> 01:45:11.080
[Guest]: think that, I as in the founders think that you could be in a kind of democratic system

01:45:11.080 --> 01:45:18.240
[Guest]: of the kind that I've described. But there could be certain kinds of people excluded

01:45:18.240 --> 01:45:23.760
[Guest]: from the very process, because the process is not perfect in some way, and their views

01:45:23.760 --> 01:45:28.960
[Guest]: therefore don't reach the fore. Now, that is not a majority minority game, necessarily,

01:45:28.960 --> 01:45:35.320
[Guest]: right? That is a game about actually a certain amount of discrimination or a certain amount

01:45:35.320 --> 01:45:42.360
[Guest]: of backwardness. And there is an attempt at the founding to say, okay, if I actually have

01:45:42.360 --> 01:45:50.560
[Guest]: a group like this, how do I identify them? Now, I don't want to identify them as belonging

01:45:50.560 --> 01:45:55.080
[Guest]: just to a particular identity. And why don't I want to do that? I don't want to do that

01:45:55.080 --> 01:45:59.960
[Guest]: for two reasons. Number one, I need some kind of principle, right? Today, somebody could

01:45:59.960 --> 01:46:04.200
[Guest]: suffer from that. Tomorrow, it could be somebody else. What's the logic? Because if I'm doing

01:46:04.200 --> 01:46:08.360
[Guest]: it, I need to explain it to the people within the group and outside the group. Second, if

01:46:08.360 --> 01:46:14.760
[Guest]: I do it purely on identity, then actually the identity I want to remove will get further

01:46:14.760 --> 01:46:20.440
[Guest]: entrenched, right? The identity I want to remove will actually be the identity that

01:46:20.440 --> 01:46:26.920
[Guest]: gets recognized, which is why the attempt then becomes to abstract a certain kind of

01:46:26.920 --> 01:46:32.880
[Guest]: concept. And the concept that they arrive at is one of backwardness. Now, the reason

01:46:32.880 --> 01:46:39.280
[Guest]: why this is linked to individual freedom in just the way that the religion question was

01:46:39.280 --> 01:46:45.440
[Guest]: is that in the religion question, the attempt is actually to focus on the individual rather

01:46:45.440 --> 01:46:49.800
[Guest]: than mediate the relationship between him or her through the group. Here, the attempt

01:46:49.800 --> 01:46:55.440
[Guest]: is to rescue the individual from the chains of a certain group pressure, right? In both

01:46:55.440 --> 01:47:01.600
[Guest]: cases, I want to recover the individual. And here the thought is that if I abstract away

01:47:01.600 --> 01:47:07.880
[Guest]: and create a category of backwardness, then I could identify people. Now, it so happens

01:47:07.880 --> 01:47:12.920
[Guest]: at that time that whatever way you slice it, certain caste groups are backward and they

01:47:12.920 --> 01:47:19.080
[Guest]: fit into that. But the identification of the caste group is actually the consequence of

01:47:19.080 --> 01:47:23.600
[Guest]: the principle. It's not the object of it, right? You have a principle and then you arrive

01:47:23.600 --> 01:47:29.600
[Guest]: at that. And the very fact that there's an emphasis on that leads to Ambedkar saying

01:47:29.600 --> 01:47:33.920
[Guest]: many important things. For instance, one of the things he says is that, look, it would

01:47:33.920 --> 01:47:42.000
[Guest]: make no sense in the world to have reservations more than 50% for the simple reason that then

01:47:42.000 --> 01:47:46.840
[Guest]: the group is not backward. Because backwardness is a relative category. If everybody's backward,

01:47:46.840 --> 01:47:50.920
[Amit Varma]: then how can you be backward? This is like the opposite of the Lake Wobegon problem,

01:47:50.920 --> 01:47:55.120
[Amit Varma]: which was if Lake Wobegon was this fictional town created by Garrison Wheeler, where everybody

01:47:55.120 --> 01:47:59.220
[Guest]: was above average. Right, exactly. And so one of the cases that the Supreme Court is

01:47:59.220 --> 01:48:06.040
[Guest]: hearing currently is a case involving 100% reservations. But Ambedkar would be horrified

01:48:06.040 --> 01:48:12.440
[Guest]: at this, right? Because the argument is that, look, actually, so the idea was that, look,

01:48:12.440 --> 01:48:19.680
[Guest]: I want to annihilate caste. I want to transcend caste. And there are certain amounts of disadvantage

01:48:19.680 --> 01:48:26.560
[Guest]: that exist that I may need to tackle in some special way. We have collapsed into a situation

01:48:26.560 --> 01:48:31.840
[Guest]: where the link between special treatment and disadvantage has been thrown out of the window.

01:48:31.840 --> 01:48:38.260
[Guest]: And instead, I want to actually split power between different caste groups. So the constitution

01:48:38.260 --> 01:48:43.720
[Guest]: has now become a power sharing device between castes, rather than actually a way to liberate

01:48:43.720 --> 01:48:49.040
[Amit Varma]: caste or liberate the individual from caste. No, and it seems to me that, you know, people

01:48:49.040 --> 01:48:54.040
[Amit Varma]: often conflate the question of caste and what reservations have become today. So if you

01:48:54.040 --> 01:48:59.440
[Amit Varma]: criticize reservations as they are today, you are immediately assumed to be casteist,

01:48:59.440 --> 01:49:03.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, which need not be the case. And I would say that the concept of caste has

01:49:03.720 --> 01:49:10.280
[Amit Varma]: also become politicized, to the extent that I can see the rationale of some of the arguments

01:49:10.280 --> 01:49:15.680
[Amit Varma]: against religious recognition in the constitution, separate electorates and reservations for

01:49:15.680 --> 01:49:20.520
[Amit Varma]: religion and so on, that those fears coming through in the context of caste, where you

01:49:20.520 --> 01:49:25.960
[Amit Varma]: are deepening divisions between people of different castes because of the politicization

01:49:25.960 --> 01:49:31.480
[Amit Varma]: of it. And therefore, you are not annihilating it if you embed it in the constitution.

01:49:31.480 --> 01:49:36.280
[Guest]: Completely, completely. I mean, it's you've now reached a situation where you're trying

01:49:36.280 --> 01:49:43.080
[Guest]: to basically have citizens compete with one another rather than hold the state accountable.

01:49:43.080 --> 01:49:47.560
[Guest]: That's absolutely correct. And I mean, you're and you're also right that the debate takes

01:49:47.560 --> 01:49:53.360
[Guest]: on a certain form, where if you criticize anything about it, even if you criticize 100%

01:49:53.360 --> 01:49:59.100
[Guest]: reservations, you're somehow against equality or against the liberation of certain groups

01:49:59.100 --> 01:50:02.440
[Guest]: that have been horrifically discriminated against, whereas Ambedkar would have been

01:50:02.440 --> 01:50:08.680
[Amit Varma]: tormented at the current caste arrangement. Exactly. Let's kind of move on to a couple

01:50:08.680 --> 01:50:15.520
[Amit Varma]: of larger questions that I had. And one is that you've set off in this book very clearly

01:50:15.520 --> 01:50:21.400
[Amit Varma]: to be a scrupulous chronicler, you know, you've chronicled it. And perhaps the only quibble

01:50:21.400 --> 01:50:25.360
[Amit Varma]: I might have against it, which is a really small quibble and which is possibly a feature

01:50:25.360 --> 01:50:29.520
[Amit Varma]: and not a bug, is that there's not enough of your perspective coming through. So is

01:50:29.520 --> 01:50:34.120
[Amit Varma]: this a conscious decision that I will not get, you know, my view of the world in this,

01:50:34.120 --> 01:50:38.480
[Amit Varma]: I'm telling a story that needs to be told. And if I leave myself out of it is better

01:50:38.480 --> 01:50:44.200
[Guest]: that way. No, I actually think there is a lot of my perspective. I think that all narratives

01:50:44.200 --> 01:50:50.320
[Guest]: have arguments embedded in them. And I think a lot of my perspective, I gesture at the

01:50:50.320 --> 01:50:57.640
[Guest]: very end, right? I don't think that the purpose of the book is so much necessarily to defend

01:50:57.640 --> 01:51:03.480
[Guest]: a particular choice. But I think it is to defend the idea that look, this is actually

01:51:03.480 --> 01:51:09.560
[Guest]: what democratic citizenship means, right, centered around general rules and the rule

01:51:09.560 --> 01:51:16.320
[Guest]: of law, centered around a state that treats people equally, and centered around citizenship

01:51:16.320 --> 01:51:23.240
[Guest]: unmediated my identity. So I think that no author can escape his or her perspective,

01:51:23.240 --> 01:51:29.040
[Guest]: as much as they might want to distance themselves from it. I think I'm all over the book. But

01:51:29.040 --> 01:51:36.200
[Guest]: I think it's also very bad for authors to explain their own work. True. I think the

01:51:36.200 --> 01:51:40.640
[Guest]: postmodern thought that the author is dead is a good one.

01:51:40.640 --> 01:51:45.400
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, I meant it in the I mean, obviously, then you have been very crafty about it. And

01:51:45.400 --> 01:51:50.840
[Amit Varma]: I meant it in the sense that while reading your chapters on centralization, or, for example,

01:51:50.840 --> 01:51:56.840
[Amit Varma]: rights and their caveats, and you summarize the arguments on both sides, so obviously,

01:51:56.840 --> 01:52:00.960
[Amit Varma]: faithfully, and with such clarity that I wasn't sure where you stood on these matters.

01:52:00.960 --> 01:52:07.520
[Amit Varma]: So, but that just means I've done well, because I've convinced you that it's them, not me.

01:52:07.520 --> 01:52:15.440
[Guest]: Ah, okay. Well, they made wrote the Constitution, not you. Yeah. So I think that there's certain,

01:52:15.440 --> 01:52:21.160
[Guest]: I think that there is an attempt at some kind of faithful reconstruction. But I think, I

01:52:21.160 --> 01:52:25.440
[Guest]: think it's like, I'll give you an example, right? I think in the centralization question,

01:52:25.440 --> 01:52:30.280
[Guest]: I think I tried to faithfully reconstruct both sides. But I also try to emphasize why

01:52:30.280 --> 01:52:35.920
[Guest]: one side lost. Right? Similarly, in the codification, I tried to capture the impulse, right? So

01:52:35.920 --> 01:52:40.880
[Guest]: I think in explaining, I think my perspective comes out in the kind of sympathy I offer

01:52:40.880 --> 01:52:43.880
[Guest]: to actually why certain things won at the end.

01:52:43.880 --> 01:52:49.640
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. Now, you know, people often would think of legal studies and legal history and

01:52:49.640 --> 01:52:54.520
[Amit Varma]: the history of the Constitution as a very dry subject. And what you're obviously dealing

01:52:54.520 --> 01:53:01.440
[Amit Varma]: with is some incredible human beings. So, you know, while you were writing this, while

01:53:01.440 --> 01:53:04.440
[Amit Varma]: you were reading everything they wrote, while you were reading about their lives, while

01:53:04.440 --> 01:53:08.240
[Amit Varma]: you were reading their debates, you know, do you go into rabbit holes when you think

01:53:08.240 --> 01:53:13.040
[Amit Varma]: about what fascinating human beings these were? And what also struck me from just, you

01:53:13.040 --> 01:53:19.360
[Amit Varma]: know, following your footnotes, and is that so many of the people who were speaking in

01:53:19.360 --> 01:53:23.400
[Amit Varma]: these debates, whether in the Constituent Assembly debates, or the larger debate of

01:53:23.400 --> 01:53:30.240
[Amit Varma]: ideas that went on were such incredible thinkers and speakers. And I don't, I contrast that

01:53:30.240 --> 01:53:36.640
[Guest]: with today and I'm like, what the fuck? No, I mean, they are incredible. And I think that

01:53:36.640 --> 01:53:41.080
[Guest]: they are remarkable human beings. And I think they have remarkable lives. And you also get

01:53:41.080 --> 01:53:45.800
[Amit Varma]: a sense of when their reasons for something are actually a rationalization for an impulse

01:53:45.800 --> 01:53:53.080
[Guest]: otherwise held. Yeah, I think you do. I mean, they one of the joys and one of the tragedies

01:53:53.080 --> 01:53:57.720
[Guest]: in some sense of working on the on a project like this is that you're exposed to extraordinary

01:53:57.720 --> 01:54:03.120
[Guest]: people. And of course, that that's a it's a joy because it's a treat. It's a tragedy

01:54:03.120 --> 01:54:08.120
[Guest]: because you realize how distant they are from the historical imagination of the current

01:54:08.120 --> 01:54:15.080
[Guest]: moment. But they have they also just have very interesting lives. I'm not sure our lives

01:54:15.080 --> 01:54:20.720
[Amit Varma]: will ever be so interesting. Yeah, they lived in different times. And as I have said a couple

01:54:20.720 --> 01:54:24.760
[Amit Varma]: of times on the show, they were responding to different incentives. So that's why you

01:54:24.760 --> 01:54:30.440
[Amit Varma]: got those kinds of politicians and not the ones you have today, who are mainly motivated

01:54:30.440 --> 01:54:35.440
[Amit Varma]: by the lust for power. So, you know, just tell me, so just looking at current times,

01:54:35.440 --> 01:54:40.640
[Amit Varma]: what is the relevance of the Constitution? And I asked this in two parts. Part one is

01:54:40.640 --> 01:54:46.000
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, it's been called a periodical and not not a book, it's so easy to change

01:54:46.000 --> 01:54:50.000
[Amit Varma]: this government might well have the numbers to do it at some point in time. What is there

01:54:50.000 --> 01:54:54.640
[Amit Varma]: for the relevance and part two is that even if it wasn't so easy to change, like you

01:54:54.640 --> 01:54:59.440
[Amit Varma]: pointed out when we were discussing free speech and the caveats, that the execution can often

01:54:59.440 --> 01:55:05.680
[Amit Varma]: stray very far away from what the Constitution intended. So if you know, what is the theory

01:55:05.680 --> 01:55:11.640
[Amit Varma]: in the Constitution is not reflected in practice in the political economy and in our society,

01:55:11.640 --> 01:55:17.720
[Guest]: then what's the point? How relevant is it? Really? I mean, I think look, it is not relevant

01:55:17.720 --> 01:55:24.000
[Guest]: in the sense that if political elites don't take it seriously, like I said, it's not relevant,

01:55:24.000 --> 01:55:27.680
[Guest]: right. And it's like one of the things I often tell people is look, the Constitution won't

01:55:27.680 --> 01:55:33.240
[Guest]: save Indian democracy, Indian democracy may save the Constitution. I think it's relevant

01:55:33.240 --> 01:55:39.880
[Guest]: because above all, it's a charter for what equality and freedom mean. Right. And I think

01:55:39.880 --> 01:55:46.440
[Guest]: it's relevant because it is a certain commitment to a certain kind of framework. And if people

01:55:46.440 --> 01:55:51.800
[Guest]: take that framework seriously, then it has the chance for a sustainable political environment.

01:55:51.800 --> 01:55:55.280
[Guest]: And it has a chance for a certain vision of freedom.

01:55:55.280 --> 01:56:00.960
[Amit Varma]: So you know, my final question, then for someone who has spent a certain amount of time living

01:56:00.960 --> 01:56:06.320
[Amit Varma]: in the past, by which I mean these decades when these debates took place, and by inhabiting

01:56:06.320 --> 01:56:11.960
[Amit Varma]: that space, and by someone who is at the same time, alive right now and seeing our modern

01:56:11.960 --> 01:56:17.920
[Amit Varma]: ferments and torments looking forward, say over a 20 year period, what gives you hope

01:56:17.920 --> 01:56:23.360
[Guest]: and what gives you despair? I think the thing that gives me hope is that

01:56:23.360 --> 01:56:34.980
[Guest]: political life is extraordinarily contingent. And that just means that even your worst fears

01:56:34.980 --> 01:56:44.840
[Guest]: may be undone by some new contingency. I think what gives me fear is the fact that it is

01:56:44.840 --> 01:56:47.960
[Guest]: only some kind of contingency that might be able to save us.

01:56:47.960 --> 01:56:51.120
[Amit Varma]: Madhav, thanks so much for coming on the show. I enjoyed reading your book and I enjoyed

01:56:51.120 --> 01:56:53.120
[Amit Varma]: chatting with you. I hope it's a first for many.

01:56:53.120 --> 01:56:57.360
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much. Thanks.

